@node  Mage/Priest Antipathy, Turn Limit, Alternate Rules, Alternate Rules
@subsubsection Mage/Priest Antipathy

The antipathy between mages and priests can be turned off.  This has the
following effects:

@table @dfn
@item 
Stacks containing priests do not receive a combat attack bonus against
stacks containing a magician or undead.  
@item
Bless Follower can be used on nobles possessing undead.
@item
The Staff of the Sun is not in play.
@item
Magicians in a province do not prevent peasants from making offerings at
temples.
@item
Priests do not receive a piety bonus for performing Last Rites on a
magician.
@item
Magicians do not receive an aura bonus for eating the body of a priest.
@item
Priests and magicians may stack together.
@end table

@node  Turn Limit, Autodrop, Mage/Priest Antipathy, Alternate Rules
@subsubsection Turn Limit

Some TAG games have a turn limit.  After a player reaches this number of
turns, he is automatically dropped from the game.

This is used primarily in the free novice game.

@node  Autodrop,  , Turn Limit, Alternate Rules
@subsubsection Autodrop

Some TAG games automatically drop a player if he does not submit orders
for his units for 3 turns in a row.  This is used primarily in free
games, to limit the number of inactive players.

@node  Winning the Game, Submitting orders, Alternate Rules, Game Mechanics
@subsection Winning the Game
Some TAG scenarios are "close-ended", which means there is a specific
way that a player (or group of players) can win the game and cause it to
end.  Other scenarios are "open-ended", which means they will continue
until no one is interested in playing any longer.

Most closed-ended TAG scenarios use the same win condition.  The game
ends when one nation conquers the world.  In particular, to win the game
a nation must achieve the following conditions for two months in a row:

@table @asis
@item (1)
No other non-neutral nations may control any provinces or cities.
Control of a province or city is given by garrisoning the province.
@item (2)
The winning nation must have twice as many NPs as all the other
non-neutral nations combined.
@end table

The win condition is checked at the end of each month.

If a scenario uses an alternate win condition, it will be stated in the
scenario description (see @ref{Scenarios}).

@node Submitting orders, Turn reports, Winning the Game, Game Mechanics
@subsection Submitting orders
Orders should be sent to @b{orders@@@var{game}.pbm.com}.  The @var{game}
part of this address will normally be something like "tag7" and will be
published in the game newsletter.

The @samp{Reply-To:} header on turn reports is set to the correct
address, so using the reply feature of your mailer should send orders to
the right place.

The orders address is read by an automated daemon which scans the orders
for syntax errors and queues them for your units.  It will send a reply
as soon as it receives mail from you, showing whether or not there were
any errors with the orders it received.

@c @group
Orders must be of the following form:

@example
@group
begin @var{player-number} @var{password}
  .
  .  @code{email}, @code{password} commands
  .

unit @var{player-number}
  .
  .  commands for player entity:  @code{name}, @code{format} or @code{quit}
  .

unit @var{unit-number}
  .
  .  commands for unit
  .

unit @var{unit-number}
  .
  .  commands for unit
  .

end
@end group
@end example

The @samp{Subject:} line on your message is ignored.

The @code{begin} keyword tells the order scanner what your player number
is.  If you have not set a password, you do not need to supply one.

The @code{unit} command replaces a set of orders for a unit.  Any
pending orders for the unit will be cleared, and the new orders sent in
will queue up.  Orders that are still executing for the unit will not be
interrupted unless the first order queued is the @code{stop} order
(@pxref{stop}).

Do not match an @code{end} for every @code{unit} command!  There should
only be one @code{end}, at the end of all of the @code{unit} sections.
The Olympia order parser will not read beyond the @code{end}.

@c @group
For example, here is a set of orders for player Fate [812], who has
two nobles, Osswid [5499] and Candide [1269]:

@example
@group
begin 812
  password sneaky

unit 5499
  explore
  move east
  explore
  study 1000

unit 1269
  move north
  stack 5499

end
@end group
@end example

The parser tries to be as flexible as possible.  It is case insensitive
and is not strict about spaces on a line, so you may use indentation to
make your orders more readable.

@c @group
Orders may be commented with the @samp{#} character.  Everything from a
@samp{#} to the end of the line will be ignored by the parser:

@example
@group
move north    # Head to Drassa to meet up with Osswid
stack 5499    # stack with him
@end group
@end example

No one will read the comments but you.  Neither the GM nor the Olympia
engine will try to interpret them for any reason.

@c @group
Note that arguments must be enclosed in quotes if they are more than one
word:

@example
@group
name "Osswid the Constructor"
@end group
@end example

The acknowledgement will show any errors that occurred while the orders
were being parsed, and list the current pending commands for all of your
units.

