@node Interrupting orders, Uncontrolled Units, Submitting orders, Submitting orders
@subsubsection Interrupting orders

@c @group
Suppose the turn report shows the following orders queued:

@example
@group
unit 5499
   # > study 2800 (executing for three more days)
   recruit 10
   explore
@end group
@end example

Sending in new orders for this unit will not disturb the still-running
study command unless the first order is @code{stop}.  For example:

@c @group
If this were sent in:

@example
@group
unit 5499
   move south
@end group
@end example

@c @group
This would be the result:

@example
@group
unit 5499
   # > study 2800 (executing for three more days)
   move south
@end group
@end example

@c @group
To interrupt the study and get on with the move right away, instead send
in:

@example
@group
unit 5499
   stop
   move south
@end group
@end example

@c @group
This will show:

@example
@group
unit 5499
   # > study 2800 (executing for three more days)
   stop
   move south
@end group
@end example

Note that the stop queues like any other order; it does not actually
interrupt the executing command until the turn runs.  This means that
the stop itself can be replaced by sending in another set of orders
later.

@node Uncontrolled Units, Order template, Interrupting orders, Submitting orders
@subsubsection Units not controlled by you (yet)

Orders may be sent in for units which are not yet under control, such as
nobles that you intend to @code{bribe} or @code{terrorize} into
switching to your faction.

As soon as the unit comes under your control, the orders queued for it
will begin to execute.

@c @group
Orders may also be sent in for new nobles which will be formed during
the turn.  First choose one of the possible unit numbers from the
choices listed near the beginning of the turn report:

@example
@group
The next five nobles formed will be:  5717 3215 4902 4489 5628
@end group
@end example

@c @group
Supply one of these numbers as the first parameter to the @code{form}
order:

@example
@group
form 5628 "Feasel the Wicked"
@end group
@end example

@c @group
Then queue some orders for Feasel to execute as soon as he appears:

@example
@group
unit 5628
  unstack
  study 2800
  move out
  recruit
  @dots{}
@end group
@end example

@node Order template, Be careful, Uncontrolled Units, Submitting orders
@subsubsection Use the order template

An order template listing all of the units for a player and showing
any pending orders for those units, appears at the bottom of the turn
sheet.

@example
@group
Order template
--------------

begin 812  # Master Bogomil's Family

unit 2508  # Tudor
   # > make 74 (still executing)

unit 2947  # Milo

unit 4375  # Beorn
   # > move s (executing for one more day)
   pillage
   recruit

unit 4763  # Sylvia

unit 5977  # Drango
   # > collect 87 0 0 (still executing)
   sail e
   sail s
   fish
   explore

unit 5418  # Comte de le Sang

end
@end group
@end example

Note that the layout of the order template matches the syntax the order
scanner expects.  Many players find it convenient to edit this template
to add or change commands for their units.  Mail everything from the
@code{begin} to @code{end} (inclusive) to the order scanner.  It is wise
to save a copy of the orders you submit in case there are errors and
they need to be resent.

@node Be careful, Failed orders, Order template, Submitting orders
@subsubsection Be careful
@display
        Against stupidity the very gods 
        Themselves contend in vain.

      @cite{Maid of Orleans}, Schiller

@end display

Beware of sending in different sets of orders too quickly.  Sometimes
messages sent within a short time of each other will arrive out of
order.  This can wreak havoc on your turn if the wrong orders arrive
last.  Compose your orders offline and review them before mailing.  A
simple typographical error in your orders could ruin your whole turn!

@node Failed orders, Player Entity, Be careful, Submitting orders
@subsubsection Failed orders

Commands that fail generally take zero time.  For instance, if
@code{study} is issued for a skill which the location does not offer, it
will fail immediately, and take zero time.  The failed @code{study}
order will not take a week, and it will not count toward the diminishing
study returns for the month.

Production commands fail immediately if none of their input resources
are available.  For instance, @code{recruit} in a location with no
peasants will immediately fail, taking zero time.  However, resources
may sometimes become depleted while the command is being executed.  In
such cases, the command may fail even after it has spent some time
executing.

@node Player Entity, Quitting the Game, Failed orders, Submitting orders
@subsubsection Player Entity

Each Olympia player faction has a number.  This number is represented by
an entity in the game.  However, unlike a noble, this entity is
mostly used as a place holder for the faction.  No one can see the
faction entity, and it can issue very few orders.

For example, suppose player Fate [xt8] has one noble Osswid [5499].
Fate does not exist in any location, so it does not receive a location
report, and no one can see it.  However, Osswid, being the player
noble for the faction, is sworn to Fate [xt8].  Fate may execute
only a limited set of administrative orders.

Nobles, not factions, issue most orders.  Do not try to @code{form}
or @code{recruit} with the player entity.  For most turns, the player
entity will have no orders queued for it.

The orders a player entity may issue are:

@itemize @bullet
@item @ref{admit}
@item @ref{format}
@item @ref{name}
@item @ref{quit}
@end itemize

@node Quitting the Game, More examples, Player Entity, Submitting orders
@subsubsection Quitting the Game

@c @group
To drop out of the game, issue the @code{quit} order for your player
entity.  For instance, player xt8 would quit by sending in the following
orders:

@example
@group
begin xt8 @var{password}
unit xt8               # don't forget @code{unit} for the player unit!
   quit

end
@end group
@end example

No turn report will be sent for the turn in which a player quits.

@node More examples, Order of nobles, Quitting the Game, Submitting orders
@subsubsection More examples

You can replace orders for some units, but leave pending orders for
other units alone, by only including @code{unit} sections for the ones
you want to change.

@c @group
If you want to see what orders are queued, but not change anything
send in:

@example
@group
begin 999               # whatever your player number is @dots{}
end
@end group
@end example

@c @group
To change your email address, send in

@example
@group
begin 999
email new@@address.com   # give your new address
end
@end group
@end example

As a security measure, the confirmation will be sent to both the new and
old addresses.

If you want to send your turn report to two or more addresses, use
both addresses in the email command, separated with a comma:

@example
@group
begin 999
email new@@address.com,other@@address.com
end
@end group
@end example

@c @group
To change the name of your faction, issue the @code{name} order for the
faction's player entity:

@example
@group
begin 999
unit 999
   name "Seekers of Fame and Power"
   @dots{}
@end group
@end example

@strong{Important}:  Don't forget the @code{unit} command for the player entity.

@node Order of nobles, Priority, More examples, Submitting orders
@subsubsection Order of nobles in a location

When a noble enters a location, it is added to the end of the list
of nobles already there.  The unit that has been in a location the
longest will appear at the top of the list.

If a noble leaves a location and later returns, it will be put at
the end of the list again.

@c @group
For example:

@example
@group
Seen here:
   Candide [1269]
   Osswid [5499]
   Feasel the Wicked [1109]
@end group
@end example

Candide has been here longest, followed by Osswid, then Feasel.  If
Candide were to leave and return, he would appear at the end of the
list.

If a noble unstacks from beneath another unit, the noble will
appear just after the unit, rather than at the end of the list.

@c @group
For example:

@example
@group
Seen here:
   Candide [1269], accompanied by:
      Osswid [5499]
   Feasel the Wicked [1109]
@end group
@end example

@c @group
Osswid is stacked beneath Candide.  If Osswid unstacks, he will appear
after Candide, not after Feasel:

@example
@group
Seen here:
   Candide [1269]
   Osswid [5499]
   Feasel the Wicked [1109]
@end group
@end example

@node Priority, Precedence, Order of nobles, Submitting orders
@subsubsection Command priority

All orders have a priority of 0-4.

@itemize @bullet
@item Permission commands (@code{admit}, @code{hostile}, etc.) are priority 0.
@item Zero time commands @footnote{A zero time command is an order which
always takes zero time. This does not include an order which may
sometimes take zero time.  For instance, @code{unstack} is always a zero
time order.  However, @code{recruit} is not, even though @code{recruit}
may terminate immediately under some conditions.}, and @code{wait}, are
priority 1.
@item @code{move} and @code{fly} are priority 2.
@item The @code{sail} and @code{study} commands are priority 4.
@item All other commands are priority 3.
@end itemize

Primarily, the order scheduler processes commands on a day-by-day basis.
Priority only orders commands within a day, and only between different
nobles.

Each day, the order scheduler will first executes all priority 1 orders
scheduled for that day. Only when all priority 1 orders are processed,
will priority 2 orders for that day be processed, then priority 3
orders, etc.  In other words, the order scheduler will not start an
order at a higher priority when an order may be started at a lower
priority.

Orders at the same priority are resolved in location order.  If two
units in a location are both waiting to start a @code{move} order, the
first unit in the location will go first.

The above description of order priorities may seem complicated, but the
intent is to let players ignore same-day synchronization issues in most
cases.  Rather that needing @code{wait} to guarantee that @code{give}
happens before @code{move}, the lower priority of @code{give} makes this
happen naturally.

@c @group
For example, consider three units stacked together, top, mid and bot:

@example
@group
top:    move ec69
        yew

mid:    unstack
        recruit

bot:    recruit
@end group
@end example

@c @group
These should be executed in the following order:

@example
@group
mid: unstack                    # unstack is prio-1
top: move ec69                  # move is prio-2
mid: recruit                    # recruit is prio-3

[top and bot arrive at ec69]

top: yew                        # yew is prio-3
bot: recruit                    # recruit is prio-3
@end group
@end example

The @code{unstack} happened first since it's a priority 1 command.  The
@code{move} went second.  When top and bot finished moving, there were
only priority three commands left, so they ran in location order.

@node Precedence, At the same time, Priority, Submitting orders
@subsubsection Command precedence within a location

@example
@group
Seen here:
   Candide [1269]
   Osswid [5499]
   Feasel the Wicked [1109]
@end group
@end example

Order precedence within a location is an advantage for commands or skill
uses which obtain resources from the location.  For instance, if Candide
and Osswid both attempted to harvest all of the lumber available in
their location, Candide would have precedence, since his harvest order
would finish before Osswid's, if they were started on the same day.

@node At the same time,  , Precedence, Submitting orders
@subsubsection At the same time @dots{}

No two things ever happen at exactly the same instant in Olympia.
Someone always goes first.

@c @group
Suppose two nobles were outside of a building (which nobody is
inside), and both wanted to enter, to claim it:

@example
@group
Seen here:
   Osswid [5499]
   Candide [1269]

Inner locations:
   Hooting Own Inn [ep76], inn
@end group
@end example

Both Osswid and Candid issue @samp{@code{move} ep76} as their first
order on day 1 of the month.  What happens?

Osswid's command begins before Candide's, since Osswid appears before
Candid in the location list.  Therefore, Osswid will enter the inn
first.

Order precedence between units in different provinces is undefined.

@example
@group
Osswid             ?            Candide
------- 8 days -------- 8 days --------
city A          city B          city C
@end group
@end example

If Osswid and Candide both leave for city B on the same day, we cannot
predict who will get their first.

@node Turn reports, Turn schedule, Submitting orders, Game Mechanics
@subsection Turn reports

A turn report will be e-mailed to you shortly after the turn is run.
Turn reports usually arrive within an hour.

The Age of Gods can produce turn reports in several different formats.
The default is text format.  This format can be read by any mail
program.

You may also receive your turn in HTML format.  This format can be read
by many mail programs, particularly Outlook and the mail readers in most
web browsers.  In this format, your turn contains many useful features
such as links between parts of the report, links to the rules, etc.

You can also receive your turn in TAGS format.  Tags are XML-like
markers in the turn intended to be read and processed by a computer
program.  You could, for instance, write a program to read this tags and
build a database of information automatically.  The TAGS format is the
same as the TEXT format, with the TAGS embedded.

Finally, you can receive your turn in RAW format.  This is format is
completely unprocessed and is intended only for people who want to build
their own post-processing tools.

For details on the various formats, see @ref{Appendix - Output Formats}.

Your turn report will also be available over the WWW.  To use this
facility, you must first set a @ref{password}.  Then you may access your
turn reports at:

@example
     http://www.pbm.com/oly/tag/reports/<your faction id>
@end example

When you access this, you'll be prompted for a user name and password.
You user name is your faction id.  If you play multiple TAG games, then
your password will correspond to the last game run.

IMPORTANT: If you give someone your password from any game, they'll have
access to all your turn reports from all the games.  Don't give out your
passwords! 

@node Turn schedule, Game Newsletter, Turn reports, Game Mechanics
@subsection Turn schedule

The turn schedule for each game is shown on the game's web page, and in
each issue of the game newsletter.  Players should receive their turn
reports by the morning following the run.

Late orders will queue for the next turn.  Beware!  Even if mailed
before the deadline, your message may take some time to get to the order
scanner.  Send your orders in a day early to avoid grief.  This will
also give you time to correct mistakes reported by the order scanner.

New player additions are performed just after the turn is run.

@node Game Newsletter, Compensation, Turn schedule, Game Mechanics
@subsection Game Newsletter

The game newsletter, (called @i{The Gods Speak}) is published with the
game turn and mailed to each player in the game.  The newsletter has
three sections: any comments or notices from the GM (if there are any),
signed press, and rumors.

Players should submit items to the newsletter with the @code{press} and
@code{rumor} commands.

The newsletter may pay gold to the player for submissions.  Check the
newsletter banner for a particular game to see if it is paying for
submissions. 

@node Compensation, Cheating, Game Newsletter, Game Mechanics
@subsection Compensation for errors

What if there's a bug which ruins your whole turn?  What if an error
in the combat system lets all of your men be killed in one day?

@itemize @bullet
@item
I will not re-run turns.  Turns can't be rerun for one player, the
entire simulation has to be run for everyone.  This takes some time and
produces a large amount of data which is mailed out.  Only for the most
serious of game disasters would I consider rerunning a turn.

@item
If you are stung by a bug, I may grant items for compensation, but I
won't alter the universe.  I might give you 1,000 gold if you are the
victim of some heinous bug, or perhaps even an NP, but I won't move a
unit that should have been in Pactra to Drassa.
@end itemize

@node Cheating, Rule changes, Compensation, Game Mechanics
@subsection Cheating

@enumerate
@item
A player may not have more than one faction in the game.
Also, multiple players from the same account are not allowed.
Each player must have their own unique email address.

@item
Players should not send in orders for another player's faction, to ruin
that person's turn or otherwise benefit.

@item
Players should not attempt to steal other player's turn reports.

@item
Players must inform the GM of any game bugs found.

@item
Anti-social behavior, including harassing telephone calls, sending
obscene/obnoxious unwanted communications, mail bombing, etc. will not
be tolerated.

@item
It is not cheating to form alliances or cooperate with players of
another nation.  It's even acceptable to occasionally act against the
interests of your nation, particularly if that serves some specific
goal.  For example, if you're trying to become a great merchant, and the
enemy offers you a bunch of gold to reveal the location of one of your
nation's large armies, you might accept.  But joining one nation with
the sole purpose of helping another nation win by being a "mole" in the
midst of the other nation is not permitted.  If you want the Imperial
Empire to win, join the Imperial Empire.

If you do choose to betray your nation, do not complain when they turn
upon you and rend your faction.  You still cannot re-join a different
nation.
@end enumerate

Punishment for serious violations is generally banishment from Olympia.
So don't cheat, do play fair, and be a good sport.

All decisions of the GM are final.

@node Rule changes, Joining, Cheating, Game Mechanics
@subsection Game additions and rule changes

Features may be added to Olympia every so often, such as new areas in
the map, NPC races, magical artifacts, skills, spells, etc.  It is also
sometimes necessary to make alterations to existing game mechanics to
correct bugs or flaws in game balance.

While it is inevitable that some players will be affected by rule
changes, every effort is made to not disrupt existing game positions.

This is mentioned only as a warning that the rules may evolve over time.
Changes are announced via email to all players.

