@node Inner Locations, Inside a City, Geography, Geography
@subsection Inner Locations

@c @group
A province may contain sublocations within its borders.  Sublocations
may usually only be entered from the surrounding province.  They will be
listed separately in the location description:

@example
@group
Inner locations:
   Carim [em28], city, 1 day
@end group
@end example

The city Carim may be entered with the @samp{@code{move} em28} order.
Travel into a city requires one day.

(@code{move in} may be used to enter a sublocation, although this order
may be ambiguous if the location contains more than one sublocation.
In such a case, the first sublocation in the Inner locations list will
be entered.  Using @code{move in} is not recommended if the entity
number of the sublocation is known.)

Nobles in a sublocation will receive a report for the surrounding
province.  However, nobles in the outer province will not normally
be able to see into an inner location without entering it.

@node Inside a City, Who else is here, Inner Locations, Geography
@subsection Inside a City

@example
@group
Carim [em28], city, in province Plain [ae48]

Routes leaving Carim [em28]:
   Out, to Plain [ae48], 1 day

Inner locations:
   Hooting Own Inn [ep76], inn
@end group
@end example

Nobles in the city Carim may @code{move out} (or @samp{@code{move}
ae48}) to the surrounding province.  They may also attempt to enter the
inn, which is a sublocation of the city.  Notice that no travel time
rating is listed for the inn; entering it takes no time (zero days).

@example
@group
move out    -or-    move ae48
move ep76
@end group
@end example

A noble in Carim will receive a location report both for the city as
well as the surrounding province Plain [ae48].  Nobles in the
Hooting Own Inn will receive a location report for the inn and one for
Carim, but will not get a report for Plain [ae48].

Nobles in a sublocation receive a report for the immediate
surrounding location.

Nobles see into inner locations without going into them.

Cities also contain markets (see @ref{Markets}), where nobles can buy
and sell goods.

@node Who else is here, More about geography, Inside a City, Geography
@subsection Who else is here?

@c @group
Nobles spotted will be listed in the location report:

@example
@group
Seen here:
   Fighters of Pelenth [2019], "carrying a gold banner"
   Osswid the Constructor [5499]
@end group
@end example

All nobles listed as being seen in the location may interact without
requiring any travel.  Thus, the Fighters of Pelenth and Osswid are
considered to be in essentially the same place.

This is true whether the nobles are in a province, a city, a ship,
an inn, or some other sublocation.

However, a noble in a sublocation may not interact with nobles
in the surrounding area.  A noble in the city must first enter the inn
before he may interact with those inside.

@node More about geography, Holes, Who else is here, Geography
@subsection More about geography

Olympian provinces are arranged in a square grid.  Travel is possible in
the four main compass points.  Thus, to move diagonally, two @code{move}
orders are required.  To move northwest, for instance, one would first
need to @samp{@code{move} n}, then @samp{@code{move} w}.

The map coordinates for a province may be read from the province's
entity number.  The row is represented by the leading two letters, the
column by the two digits.  The northwest corner is [aa00], with rows
increasing to the south, and columns increasing to the east.

For example, a world 100 by 100 provinces would be numbered:

@example
@group
    00   01   02  @dots{} 99
  +----------------------
aa|
ab|         ab02
ac|    ac01 ac02     ac99
@dots{}
@dots{}
dv|         dv02
@end group
@end example

Entity numbers for sublocations do not correspond to any coordinate
system.

The map wraps at all edges.  Traveling west from ac00 will lead to ac99,
for instance.

@node Holes, Hidden routes, More about geography, Geography
@subsection Holes in the Map

The map has some @dfn{holes}, representing impassable provinces.  Routes
into some provinces may also be hidden.

@example
@group
Plain [cd21], plain, in region Tollus

Routes leaving Plain [cd21]:
   North, to Plain [cc21], 7 days
   East, to Plain [cd22], 7 days
   West, to Plain [cd20], 7 days
@end group
@end example

Notice the lack of a southern exit.  This means that there is no known
southern route from Plain [cd21], into what should be Plain [ce21].
Exploration may find a southern route, but it is possible that none may
ever be found, and the terrain to the south is completely impassable.

@node Hidden routes, Ocean ports, Holes, Geography
@subsection Hidden routes

If exploration finds a hidden route, any noble in the player's faction
will be able to use it.

@example
@group
> explore
A hidden route has been found!

   South, to Plain [ce21], 7 days
@end group
@end example

@c @group
The location description for this place will now include the hidden
route:

@example
@group
Plain [cd21], plain, in region Tollus

Routes leaving Plain [cd21]:
   North, to Plain [cc21], 7 days
   South, to Plain [ce21], 7 days, hidden
   East, to Plain [cd22], 7 days
   West, to Plain [cd20], 7 days
@end group
@end example

However, units from other factions, even if they know that the hidden
route's entity number is [ce21], will not be able to travel across it.

All factions with units in a stack traveling across a hidden route, with
the exception of units being held prisoner, will learn of its existence.
Nobles from factions wanting to learn how to use the hidden route can
stack with a noble about to move across the route.

@node Ocean ports, Port Cities, Hidden routes, Geography
@subsection Ocean ports

A ship in an ocean province may sail into an adjoining land
province.

@example
@group
Ocean [cw12], ocean, in South Sea

Routes leaving Ocean [cw12]:
   North, to Ocean [cv12], Atnos Sea, 4 days
   East, to Mountain [cw13], West Camaris, impassable
   South, to Plain [cx12], West Camaris, 1 day
   West, to Ocean [cw11], 4 days

Inner locations:
   Island [eb97], island, 1 day
@end group
@end example

A ship sailing in this ocean province may dock by sailing to Plain
[cx12] or Island [eb97].

Ships may not dock in mountain provinces, as the rocky cliffs are too
dangerous to approach.  Routes between ocean and mountain provinces are
marked @samp{impassable}.


@node Port Cities, Example city description, Ocean ports, Geography
@subsection Port Cities

A city in a province adjoining an ocean will have been founded on the
best spot for an ocean port.  The ocean will only be accessible through
the port city in this case, and not through the surrounding region.

@example
@group
