@node  Allowing stacking,  , Stacking, Stacking
@subsection Allowing stacking

By default, a unit may not stack with a noble belonging to another
faction.  A unit is also denied entry to a location controlled by
another player if that location's border is closed.

Players may allow units from other factions to stack with them or enter
buildings or ships they control with the @code{admit} order.  (See also
@ref{Control of Locations}).

@node Carrying capacity and Travel, Ships, Stacking, Movement
@section Carrying capacity and Travel
Men and items are rated for how much they weigh, and how much they can
carry, walking, riding or flying.

@example
@group
                weight   walking    riding   flying
                ------   -------    ------   ------
noble             100      100        -         -
peasant           100      100        -         -
worker            100      100        -         -
riding horse      300      300       150        -
wild horse        300      self      self       -
warmount          300      400       200        -
ox               1000     1500       self       -
winged horse      300      150       150       150
lt. wagon	  500     1000       500*	-
hvy. wagon	  900     1800       900	-
war wagon	  900     1800       900*	-

* Light and war wagons cannot move at riding pace in mountains or swamps.
@end group
@end example

Note that the only men that will carry anything are peasants, workers
and nobles.  Military units (such as knights) refuse to demean
themselves by acting as packhorses.  Skirmishers are simply too
unreliable and drunken to carry anything.

In order to ride, the total riding capacity must cover the weights of
all the units that may not ride themselves.

Examples:
@table @asis
@item peasant + riding horse
@display
ride capacity is 150 - 100 = 50
walk capacity is 300 + 100 = 400
@end display

@item peasant + riding horse + wild horse
@display
ride capacity is 150 - 100 + 0 = 50
walk capacity is 100 + 300 + 0 = 400
@end display

The wild horse can walk or ride on its own, but will not carry anything.

@item peasant + riding horse + ox
@display
ride capacity is 150 - 100 = 50
walk capacity is 100 + 300 + 1500 = 1900
@end display

The ox may be driven alongside the horse, but will not carry anything
when moving so quickly.
@end table

A stack will ride if there is enough riding capacity to carry all of the
non-riders.  Otherwise, the stack will walk.  (See also @ref{Swamps}.)

In order to fly, the total flying capacity for the stack must cover the
weights of all units that can not fly themselves.

Stacks which are overloaded beyond their walking capacity will travel
slower than normal.  A stack loaded at 150% of its walking capacity will
take 50% longer to traverse a route.  Stacks overloaded to over 200% of
walking capacity may not travel at all.

Weights and capacities are always considered for the stack as a whole.
One unit may have all the men, and another unit may have all the horses.
If they are stacked together, the distribution of items across units is
irrelevant.

