There are several commands useful for operating a commercial ferry:

@table @code
@item fee
Sets the fee passengers will be charged
@item board
Passengers use this to pay their fee and board a ferry
@item unload
Unload passengers once the destination is reached
@item ferry
Signals passengers waiting in port that they may board
@end table

The captain of a ferry uses the @code{fee} command to set the fee
charged to passengers boarding his ship (see @xref{fee}).  The fee can
be expressed in terms of the number of nobles boarding, the number of
men boarding, the weight boarding or any combination of the three.

For instance, if the captain wanted to charge 1/2 gold per unit weight
of the passenger's stack, he would issue @samp{@code{fee} weight 500}.
(a 500 gold fee for every 10000 weight).

Note that like any fee, the fee set for a ferry will not take effect
until the end of the month.

The fee is a property of the ship, not the captain, but will be cleared
when the last noble leaves the ship.  The fee may also be cleared with
the @code{fee} command.  If no fee is set, then the ship is not
considered to be operating as a ferry, and nobles are may not use
the @code{board} order to enter the ship.

Passengers issue @samp{@code{board} @var{ship}} to board a ferry.  The
order will fail if the ship is not present, or if it is not operating as
a ferry (the captain of the ship has no fee set).  @code{board} will
cause the noble to pay the captain the required boarding fee, then
move the noble's stack onto the ship.

The @code{board} command also prevents the ship from being overloaded.
A stack that would overload the ship is turned away.

Note that the @code{board} command, unlike the @code{move} command,
ignores the admit list of the ship's captain.

@node Ferry synchronization,  , Operating a ferry, Ships
@subsection Ferry synchronization

Suppose now that the captain has a ship, has set a fee, announced his
service in the @i{Game Newsletter} and with @code{post}, and is now
ready to ferry passengers.  What should he tell them?  How will the
synchronization work?

Passengers should travel to the port the ferry will be arriving at and
issue @samp{@code{wait ferry} @var{ship}}.

When the ship arrives at port, the captain should order @code{unload} to
eject his current load of passengers, then @code{ferry} to signal any
passengers waiting in port that they may now board.

Note that passengers should not use @code{wait ship} to wait for the
ferry.  Otherwise, they will attempt to @code{board} as soon as the ship
reaches the port.  The captain's @code{unload} order may not have
executed at this point.  In this case, @code{board} orders might fail
because there won't be any room to enter the ship until the existing
load of passengers has disembarked.

@c @group
Example:

@example
@group
Posted by Captain McCook [3402]:
"Captain McCook's ferry to Drassa departs each
 Sunsear on the 15th.  The fee is 1 gold/wt.
 Issue WAIT FERRY ht34 then BOARD ht34 for
 ferry service.   Arrr!"
@end group
@end example

@c @group
Captain McCook's orders:

@example
@group
> fee wieght 1000                 # 1 gold/wt. is our fee
> sail @dots{}                # arrival at port
> unload                  # unload current passengers
> wait day 15             # wait until stated time of departure
> ferry                   # sound our horn
> sail @dots{}                # on to the next port
@end group
@end example

@c @group
Passengers wishing to travel on McCook's ferry:

@example
@group
> wait ferry ht34             # [ht34] is McCook's ship
> board ht34                  # pay our gold and embark
> wait loc @var{destination}          # Captain McCook will @code{unload} us at the
                              # end of the journey, so wait until we
                              # find ourselves in the destination city.
@end group
@end example

