       10  peasants [10]          1,000  cap 1,000 (1,1,0)
      195  wood [77]              5,850  

hj2l in Great Forest [ba13]
-----------------------------------
        6  peasants [10]            600  cap 600 (1,1,0)
@end group
@end example

Garrisons do not monitor activity in hidden locations, even if the
players who rule over the garrisons have discovered the hidden
locations.

The @samp{@code{decree watch} @var{who}} order may be given by a ruler
to instruct all garrisons to watch for a particular unit.  This is
useful for locating individuals who would otherwise go unnoticed by the
garrisons.

@node Referring to garrisons, Status, Garrison reports, Control of Provinces
@subsubsection Referring to garrisons

Since a province may only have one garrison, garrisons may be referred
to without knowing their entity number.  The keyword @code{garrison}
will match the province's garrison, if there is one.

@c @group
Examples:

@example
@group
give garrison 12 5
attack garrison
@end group
@end example

@node Status, Province Control, Referring to garrisons, Control of Provinces
@subsubsection Status

@c @group
The number of provinces a noble controls determines his status or rank
and allows all the nobles in that faction to control additional men in battle:

@example
@group
provinces       rank            control
---------       ----            -------
   1-3          lord              +4
   4-7          knight            +5
   8-11         baron             +6
  12-15         count             +7
  16-19         earl              +8
  20-22         marquess          +9
   23+          duke             +10
  region        king             +20   (region must have at
                                        least 25 provinces)
@end group
@end example

In addition, if a noble has control over every province in a region,
and the region contains at least 25 provinces, then the noble is
given the rank of king.

@node Province Control, Province Entrance Fees, Status, Control of Provinces
@subsubsection Province Control

Border control for provinces is the same as border control for
sublocations (see @ref{Permission to Enter}), with some exceptions.

First, the owner of a province is the first noble in the castle to which
the province's garrison is pledged.

Second, the owner of a province also controls any city within the
province.

Third, in case of attack, the province and the city are defended by the
garrison, not by the first unit in the location.

Fourth, the garrison will not patrol the border (leaving it open) unless
there is a noble seated in the controlling castle.

@node Province Entrance Fees, Taxes, Province Control, Control of Provinces
@subsubsection Province Entrance Fees

The owner of a province may set an entrance fee for the province or any
city in the province (see @ref{Entrance Fees}).

The entrance fees for the province and any city in the province are paid
to the garrison.

The garrison will not collect entrance fees unless there is a noble
seated in the controlling castle.

@node Taxes, Province Tax, Province Entrance Fees, Control of Provinces
@subsubsection Taxes

A noble who controls a province may raise money by placing a general tax
on the province and/or by placing a market tax on any city in the
province.

@menu
