@node accept, admit, Appendix - Command listing, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{accept}
@cartouche
@example
@code{accept} @var{from-who} @var{item} [@var{qty}]
@code{accept} @var{nation} @var{item} [@var{qty}]
@code{accept} clear
@bullet{} time: 0 days
@bullet{} priority: 0
@end example
@end cartouche

The ACCEPT order must be used in order to receive items from other
players. Gold is exempt from the ACCEPT check.

If ACCEPT is issued by a noble, it applies to items given to that
noble only. If ACCEPT is issued by the player entity, it applies to
every unit in the faction.

If from-who is 0, the item will be accepted from anyone. Otherwise
from-who should specify a noble, a faction, or a nation name. If item is
0, any item will be accepted. If qty is zero or is not present, any
quantity of the item will be accepted.

If qty is specified, the given quantity must be less than or equal to
the qty specified on the matching ACCEPT order. If the GIVE is
successful, the given quantity will be deduced from the remaining qty
value in the outstanding ACCEPT.

A GIVE which could be passed by multiple overlapping ACCEPT orders will
choose the first which matches, first for the noble, then for the
player entity. If an ACCEPT order specifies an item quantity limit, the
quantity must be greater than or equal to the amount specified in the
GIVE order. Multiple conflicting ACCEPT orders will not combined to
satisfy a single GIVE.

"ACCEPT CLEAR" is used to clear all existing accepts.  If used by a
noble, it clears all accepts for the noble.  If used by the player
entity, it clears all the player-level accepts.

Examples: 

@example
     ACCEPT 0 0              # accept anything from anyone
     ACCEPT Mandor 0         # accept anything from Mandorians
     ACCEPT 0 10             # accept peasants from anyone
     ACCEPT 2950 0           # accept anything from noble 2950
     ACCEPT 2950 10          # accept peasants from noble 2950
     ACCEPT 2950 10 5        # accept up to 5 peasants from
                             # noble 2950
     ACCEPT Pen 10 5         # accept up to 5 peasants from Pen
     ACCEPT 501 10           # accept peasants from any noble
                             # in faction 501
     ACCEPT 501 10 5         # accept up to 5 peasants from
                             # nobles in faction 501
     ACCEPT clear	     # clear all existing accepts
@end example

The current status of what a noble will accept is shown in the turn
report.  The turn report first lists what the noble will specifically
accept and then any accepts that he inherits from the player entity:

@example
  Accepting:

      Accepting any amount of iron [76] from The Duchess [yy6].
      (Accepting any amount of anything from any member of Mandor
      Confederacy.)
@end example

In this case, the noble is specifically accepting iron from another
player, and the entire faction is accepting anything from any member of
the Mandor Confederacy.

@node admit, attack, accept, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{admit}
@cartouche
@example
@code{admit} @var{who} [@samp{ALL}] [@var{nation | units}]
@bullet{} time: 0 days
@bullet{} priority: 0
@end example
@end cartouche

Allow units to stack with @var{who}.  By default, a unit may not stack
with a noble belonging to another faction.  This command gives
permission to other units to stack with @var{who}.

For example, suppose that Drakkar the Trader [1752] wants to stack with
Feasel the Wicked [1109].  They belong to different factions, so Drakkar
cannot stack with Feasel until Feasel gives him permission.

@example
@group
admit 1109 1752    # permit [1752] to stack with [1109]
@end group
@end example

This command also permits units to enter locations controlled by
@var{who}.  By default, a unit may enter any location unless the border
is closed (see @ref{border}).  If the border is closed, only units which
can stack with the noble that controls the location will be permitted to
enter the location.

For example, suppose that Feasel the Wicked [1109] is in The Old Tower
[a1i] and has closed the border.  Drakkar cannot enter the tower unless
Feasel puts Drakkar on his admit list:

@example
@group
admit 1109 1752    # permit [1752] to enter locations controlled by [1109]
@end group
@end example

Once he's done this, Drakkar can enter the tower.  Note that Drakkar can
also stack with Feasel.  There's currently no way to admit someone to a
location without also giving them permission to stack.

A common mistake is to admit Drakkar to the location, e.g.,

@example
        admit a1i 1752  # permit [1752] to enter [a1i] WRONG!
@end example

Admitting someone to a structure or location does nothing.  You must
admit them to the noble that controls the location, not to the location
itself. 

There are three cases for the rest of @code{admit}'s arguments:

(1) If no further arguments are given, @code{admit} will clear the
permissions for the given entity, and deny admission or stacking to any
foreign unit:

@example
@group
admit ce90                  # allow no one to stack with ce90
@end group
@end example

(2) If a list of units, players, or nations is given, those units will
be permitted to stack with @var{who} or enter any location @var{who}
controls:

@example
@group
admit ce90 778 2960 4240    # allow any member of faction 778,
                            # as well as 2960 and 4240, to stack with ce90
admit ce90 mandor 4481      # admit Mandorians and 4481
@end group
@end example

Note that if a faction is specified, units within the faction must not be
concealing their lord in order to be recognized.

(3) If the keyword @samp{ALL} is used, then permission is granted to
everyone:

@example
@group
admit ce90 all                  # allow anyone to stack with ce90
@end group
@end example

A list of units to exclude may follow @samp{ALL}:

@example
@group
admit ce90 all 778 2960 4240    # allow anyone to stack with ce90, except
                                # any member of faction 778, and
                                # units 2960 and 4240.
admit ce90 all Pen		# Admit all, except Pen.
@end group
@end example

Summary examples:

@example
@group
admit ce90              # admit no one to ce90
admit ce90 all          # admit anyone to ce90
admit ce90 778          # admit any member of faction 778 to ce90
admit ce90 all 778      # admit anyone but a member of faction 778
admit ce90 2960 4240    # admit 2960 or 4240 to ce90
admit ce90 mandor       # admit anyone from Mandor
admit ce90 mandor 2960  # admit anyone from Mandor and 2960
@end group
@end example

@c @group
If there are too many units to list on a line with a single @code{admit}
order, more @code{admit} orders may be used:

@example
@group
admit ce90 2596 3921 3934 3999 4012 4045 4046 4256 4300
@end group
@end example

has the same meaning as:

@example
@group
admit ce90 2596 3921 3934 3999 4012
admit ce90 4045 4046 4256 4300
@end group
@end example

Don't forget to give the entity again as the first argument on
continuation @code{admit} orders!  (ce90 in the above example)

Note that in TAG, @emph{unlike other versions of Olympia}, the first
admit order of a turn does not clear the admits for a unit!  The only
time admits for a unit are cleared is when admit is used with no
arguments, e.g.,

@example
        admit g83
@end example

clears the admit list for [g83].

Only @code{admit} permissions of the top most noble of a stack are
considered.  Other units which do not have @code{admit} permission may
accompany a noble who does.
