@node bribe, build, breed, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{bribe}
@cartouche
@example
@code{bribe} @var{who} @var{amount} [@var{flag}]
@bullet{} time: 7 days
@bullet{} priority: 3
@end example
@end cartouche

Offer a noble gold in an attempt to win their service.  The
Persuasion subskill Bribe noble [1301] is required to use the
@code{bribe} order.  The amount must be at least 250 gold, or the
receiving noble will not consider it a serious offer.

Nobles with oathbound loyalty ignore bribes.  They may accept the
gift, but they will not renounce loyalty to their lord.

Nobles with contract loyalty will accept the bribe if it exceeds their
current loyalty rating.  For example, a noble of loyalty contract-750
would ignore any bribe of less than 751 gold.

Nobles with fear loyalty will accept any bribe of at least 250 gold.

Note that "refugee" nobles may have any sort of loyalty (oath, contract,
or fear).

If the bribe is successful, the noble will renounce loyalty to his
current lord, and swear fealty to the bribing noble.  Nobles who are
successfully bribed will have contract loyalty of half the amount of the
bribe over their old loyalty.  For example, a noble with contract
loyalty of 570 who was bribed with 1100 gold would switch loyalties and
have a new loyalty of contract-265 ((1100-570)/2).  Nobles with fear
loyalty before the bribe are treated as if they had contract-250
loyalty.

If flag is 1, and the bribe attempt is successful, the bribed
noble will stack with the briber.

Bribes will be refused by nobles who have already switched
lords during the month because of bribery.  For example, suppose
Osswid successfully bribes Feasel, and Feasel swears loyalty to
Osswid.  Later that turn, if Procrustes attempts to bribe Feasel,
Feasel will refuse to accept the bribe.

@c @group
Examples:

@example
@group
bribe 5499 750      # Offer [5499] 750 gold to switch factions.
                    # If successful, [5499] will not stack with the
                    # briber.

bribe 3409 300 1    # Offer [3409] 300 gold to switch factions.
                    # If successful, [3409] will stack with the briber.
@end group
@end example


@node build, buy, bribe, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{build}
@cartouche
@example
@code{build} @var{structure} "@var{Name}" [@var{max-days}] [@var{identifier}]
@code{build} @var{structure} [@var{max-days}]
@code{build} ship "@var{Name}" @var{hulls} [@var{max-days}] [@var{identifier}]
@code{build} ship [@var{max-days}]
@bullet{} time: varies
@bullet{} priority: 3
@end example
@end cartouche

@c @group
Build the indicated structure or ship.  All construction tasks require
at least three workers to begin.  The noble should acquire the
required quantity of building material, unstack from beneath other
nobles, and issue one of the following build commands:

@example
@group
build inn "@var{name of inn}" 
build shaft "@var{name of mine}" 
build temple "@var{name of temple}" 
build tower "@var{name of tower}" 
build castle "@var{name of castle}"
build ship "@var{name of ship}" @var{number of hulls}
@end group
@end example

Note that you are *required* to provide a name when starting a building,
and a name and a number of hulls when starting a ship.  If you do not
provide a name and/or a number of hulls, the build command will likely
fail.

Any of these commands can be followed by the maximum number of days to
spend building, or the maximum number of days and an identifier (see
below).

For example, to start building a castle, one might issue:

@example
@group
build castle "Castle Blood"
@end group
@end example

or

@example
@group
build castle "Castle Blood" 14
@end group
@end example

indicating that the noble should build for 14 days, or 

@example
@group
build castle "Castle Blood" 14 aj4
@end group
@end example

indicating that the noble should build for 14 days and the id "aj4"
should be used.

If you wish to specify an identifier for the building, but not a maximum
number of days to work, you should use zero for the maximum number of
days, e.g., 

@example
@group
build castle "Castle Blood" 0 aj4
@end group
@end example

Do not simply leave out the maximum number of days:

@example
@group
build castle "Castle Blood" aj4
@end group
@end example

This will be misinterpreted by the game, with unpredictable results.

A new structure or ship will be created, and the builder will be placed
inside.  Construction proceeds until completed unless maximum days has
been specified.  

@example
@group
kind        effort    material   skill         where
----        ------    --------   -----         -----
inn            300     75 wood    1400         province or city
mine shaft     500        none    1703         mountain or mine shaft
temple       1,000    50 stone    1400         anywhere
tower        2,000   100 stone    1400         anywhere
castle      10,000   500 stone    1400         province or city
city	    50,000  2000 stone    1490	       province
                     500 wood
ship hull      100    10 wood     1002         port or ocean province   
@end group
@end example

Effort is in worker-days.

Construction [1400] is required to erect buildings.  Build Hull [1002], a
subskill of Shipcraft [1000], is required to build ships.  Mines may be
built with Build Mine Shaft [1703].

To resume construction on a ship or building, enter the uncompleted
structure and use one of the following commands:

@example
@group
build inn 
build shaft 
build temple 
build tower 
build castle 
build ship 
@end group
@end example

Note that when resuming work you do not specify a name (or the number of
hulls for a ship).  Any of these commands can also be followed by a
maximum number of days to work.

Do not include the name of the structure when resuming work (or the
number of hulls).  This will be misinterpreted by the game with
unpredictable results.

The first tower a player builds requires no workers, no stone, and only
takes a day to build.

If the player specifies an identifier for a structure, it must be drawn
from the list of identifiers for new nobles listed at the top of the
player's turn report:

@example
@group
The next five nobles formed will be:  af8 8e8 ae8 a8e a88
@end group
@end example

Note that this identifier follows the maximum days (and possibly the
number of hulls), so these must be specified as well.  For example, to
build a tower using one of your assigned identifiers and to work on it
until completed, you would use the command:

@example
@group
build tower "My Tower" 0 ae8
@end group
@end example

Here, maximum days is specified as zero as a "placeholder" so that the
game correctly understand that you intend "ae8" to be the identifier for
the new tower.

For more details, see @ref{Buildings} and @ref{Ships}.

@node buy, catch, build, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{buy}
@cartouche
@example
@code{buy} @var{item} @var{qty} @var{price} [@var{have-left}]
@bullet{} time: 0 days
@bullet{} priority: 1
@end example
@end cartouche

Buy @var{quantity} of the given item for no more than @var{price} each.

If @var{quantity} is zero, any pending @code{buy} order for the
indicated item will be canceled.

Only one pending @code{buy} order may be active for each item at a time.
If two @code{buy} orders are issued for the same item, and the first has
not yet completed, the second @code{buy} order will replace the first.

Buys and sells are only matched in cities, where markets may be found to
execute trades.  However, @code{buy} and @code{sell} may be issued
anywhere.

Trades only occur at the end of the day.  Therefore, you must stay in a
location for at least one day to execute a trade.  If you step into a
market, issue a @code{buy} or @code{sell}, and then leave immediately,
no trade will occur.  To be certain to stay at least one day, you may
issue a @ref{wait} command.

@c @group
Example:

@example
@group
> buy 79 3 5
Try to buy three iron [79] for 5 gold each.
@end group
@end example

@c @group
If there is a seller of iron in the city, selling for 5 gold
or less, the trade will be executed:

@example
@group
1: Bought three iron [79] for 15 gold.
@end group
@end example

@c @group
Otherwise, the buy will be placed on the noble's pending trades
list:

@example
@group
Pending trades:

trade    price    qty   item
-----    -----    ---   ----
buy        5      3   iron [79]
@end group
@end example

@c @group
At the end of the turn, the buy order will appear in the city's market
report:

@example
@group
Market report:

trade    who    price    qty   item
-----    ---    -----    ---   ----
  buy   2019        5      3   iron [79]
@end group
@end example

A trade will match between a buyer and a seller if the buyer's price is
greater than or equal to the seller's price.  The actual price that the
trade will be made at is the seller's price.

Have-left is an amount of gold that the noble will not spend on this
trade.  For instance, if the unit issued @code{buy} 79 2 10 5, this
would mean @samp{Buy two iron [79] for 10 gold each, but not if I'll
have less than 5 gold left over.}  If the noble had 15 gold, only
one of the iron would be bought.

@node catch, claim, buy, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{catch}
@cartouche
@example
@code{catch} [@var{number of horses}] [@var{days}]
@bullet{} time: as given
@bullet{} priority: 3
@end example
@end cartouche

Attempt to catch any wild horses found roaming the plains or in a
pasture.  Each day the noble will have a 25% chance of catching a wild
horse, if any can be found.

Each plains or pasture location contains a population of horses.  Plains
provinces can support 100 wild horses, while pastures, being smaller,
can support only 20 horses.  At the end of each month, the horse
population breeds new horses.  In plains, one new horse is bred each
month.  In pastures, where forage is better, three new horses are born
each month.

If the population of horses in any location drops to zero, it will take
some time for the horse population to recover.  A noble can add wild
horses to a location by dropping them from his inventory in that location.

A unit must know the Catch wild horses [1930] subskill of Ranger
[1900] in order to catch horses.

@c @group
Examples:

@example
@group
catch        # catch as many horses as possible
catch 1      # stop after catching 1 wild horse
catch 0 10   # try to catch horses for 10 days
catch 1 10   # stop after catching 1 wild horse, or 10 days,
             # whichever comes first
@end group
@end example

In all cases, horse-catching ceases when no more horses can be found
roaming the plains.  @code{catch} is an alias for @samp{@code{collect}
51}.

@node claim, collect, catch, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{claim}
@cartouche
@example
@code{claim} @var{item} [@var{number}]
@bullet{} time: 0 days
@bullet{} priority: 1
@end example
@end cartouche

New players are given a few things to get them started.  Rather than
load them with possessions when they first set foot in the world,
slowing their travel and make them tempting targets for bandits, they
may obtain these items at any time with the @code{claim} command.

New players are given:

@example
@group
5,000 gold [1]
   50 wood [77]
@end group
@end example

Any unit in the player's faction may claim the items.

@example
@group
> claim 77
Claimed 50 wood.
> claim 1 1000
Claimed 1,000 gold.
@end group
@end example

In the Eight Kings scenario, players can purchase items to put in their
initial claim.  See @ref{The Eight Kings Scenario}.

In some games, players may put gold into their claim by using the
@ref{give} command.  To do this, have your noble give the gold to your
faction id.  For example, if you are faction [x8x], then

@example
@group
> give x8x 1 100
@end group
@end example

There is a 10% fee collected when placing gold into claim, so in this
case the actual deposit would only be 90 gold.

@node collect, contact, claim, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{collect}
@cartouche
@example
@code{collect} @var{item} [@var{number}] [@var{days}]
@bullet{} time: as given
@bullet{} priority: 3
@end example
@end cartouche


Catch, harvest, collect or produce the given item from the unit's
current location, if possible.  Collection proceeds until the desired
quantity of the item has been obtained, or the given number of days has
passed, whichever comes first.

If neither number or days is given, @code{collect} will continue until
the location's supply of the item is fully depleted.

Collection ceases when no more of the resource is available in the
location.  Thus, @samp{@code{collect} 87 10} may obtain less than 10
fish [87], if the current ocean province's supply of fish runs out.

@c @group
Examples:

@example
@group
collect 10         # Recruit as many peasants [10] as possible
collect 68 2       # Harvest two yew trees
collect 87 0 10    # Fish for 10 days
collect 87 25 10   # Fish until 25 fish [87] have been caught, or
                   # for 10 days, whichever comes first
@end group
@end example

@c @group
Many collection commands have aliases so they can be more easily
remembered.  For example, the above orders could be written:

@example
@group
recruit
yew 2
fish 0 10
fish 25 10
@end group
@end example

Most collection tasks require the unit to possess a particular skill,
and to be in a likely location to obtain the desired item.

@example
@group
num  item        who     where            qty  skill  chance  alias
---  ----        ---     -----            ---  -----  ------  -----
 10  peasant     noble   city, province@footnote{forest, plains or mountain} 10   none   100%   @code{recruit}
 68  yew         worker  yew groves         5   1603   100%   @code{yew}
 77  wood        worker  forest            30   1602   100%   @code{wood}
 78  stone       worker  mountains         50   1402   100%   @code{quarry}
 78  stone       worker  rocky hills       10   1402   100%   @code{quarry}
 78  stone       worker  desert            10   1402   100%   @code{quarry}
 87  fish        sailor  ocean             50   1004    50%   @code{fish}
 51  wild horse  noble   plains             @footnote{See "Catch wild horses [1930]"}   1930    25%   @code{catch}
@end group
@end example

Other rare items which may be collected are listed in 
Collect rare foliage [1604], a subskill of Forestry [1600], and
Collect rare elements [1503], a subskill of Alchemy [1500].

Explanation of table columns:
@table @dfn
@item num
@itemx item
The resource to be collected.  For example, Fish [87].

@item who
Some tasks may only be performed by a noble, while others must be done
by men, such as workers or sailors.  For instance, recruiting requires
the attention of a noble.  Additional men are of no benefit.

Fishing, however, requires sailors.  The noble himself does not
participate.  The more sailors available for fishing, the quicker the
fish will be caught.

@item where
@itemx qty
Resources are replenished at the end of each month.  Each ocean province
will have 50 fish that may be caught.  Mountains yield up to 50 stone
per turn.

@item skill
@c @group
Skills are required for most collection tasks (except recruiting):

@example
@group
activity        subskill                  category
--------        --------                  --------
recruiting      none                      none
cutting yew     Harvest yew [1603]        Forestry [1600]
cutting timber  Harvest lumber [1602]     Forestry [1600]
quarrying       Stone quarrying [1402]    Construction [1400]
fishing         Fishing [1004]            Shipcraft [1000]
horse catching  Catch wild horses [1930]  Ranger [1900]
@end group
@end example


@item chance
The rate of collection is certain for most tasks.  Cutting timber yields
one wood [77] per day per worker, as long as the forest has a supply of
wood.

However, some tasks have an element of randomness.  Horse-catching, for
example, is a difficult, uncertain task.  Each day there is only a 25%
chance that a noble will catch a wild horse.

The chance is for the unit as a whole, not for individual men engaged in
the task.  Thus, a unit of sailors will collect fish about half of the
days they spend fishing.  The other half, no fish will be caught.

@item alias
@c @group
Common collection tasks have an alias so they are easier to remember.

@example
@group
task            alias
----            -----
@code{collect} 10      @code{recruit}
@code{collect} 68      @code{yew}
@code{collect} 77      @code{wood}
@code{collect} 78      @code{quarry}
@code{collect} 87      @code{fish}
@code{collect} 51      @code{catch}
@end group
@end example

For example, the orders @samp{@code{collect} 51 0 10} and
@samp{@code{catch} 0 10} are equivalent.
@end table

@c @group
Note that if no arguments are supplied to the @code{collect} order (or
one of its aliases), it may never terminate.  For instance, suppose a
unit with one sailor fishes alone in an ocean province:

@example
@group
fish    -or-    collect 87
@end group
@end example

Since no arguments were given for the @code{fish} order, fishing will
continue as long as the ocean has a supply of fish.  The sailor will
produce, on average, a fish every two days, or 15 fish per month.  Since
this is less than the monthly supply of fish in an ocean province, the
sailor will never exhaust the supply, and thus is likely to continue
fishing forever, until interrupted with a @code{stop} order.

@node contact, decree, collect, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{contact}
@cartouche
@example
@code{contact} @var{who}
@bullet{} time: 0 days
@bullet{} priority: 0
@end example
@end cartouche

Used by nobles hidden through stealth, magic, or because of fog to
inform other units of their presence.

For example, if Osswid [5501] is employing stealth skills to hide, he
will not be visible to other nobles.  Orders issued by other units
referencing [5501] will fail.

However, Osswid may desire to allow certain units to interact with him
while he is hidden.  If this is the case, he should issue @code{contact}
orders for those units to be informed of his presence.

The @code{contact} order may also be specify a player number.  In this
case, every unit in the specified player's faction will be aware of the
hidden unit's presence.

Contact information is maintained until the hidden unit moves.  Once the
unit has moved, it must issue new @code{contact} orders if other units
are to continue to be able to interact with it.

The @code{contact} order is silent; it does not provide a message to the
contacted player or faction.

Units belonging to the same player are always aware of each other's
presence.  They do not need to use @code{contact}.

Hidden units are not shown in the location report, even if their
presence has been reveal through @code{contact} or @code{seek}.

Related orders: @ref{seek}

@node decree, dedicate, contact, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{decree}
@cartouche
@example
@code{decree} @var{decree} @var{who}
@bullet{} time: 0 days
@bullet{} priority: 0
@end example
@end cartouche

Issue a decree to all garrisons that the noble controls.  There is no
way to issue selective decrees to individual garrisons; all garrisons
under control receive the same decree.

The decree may be one of the following:
@table @dfn
@item watch
Instruct the garrisons to watch for the given unit.  Each garrison may
accept up to three @code{decree watch} order per month.  Additional
watch decrees are ignored.

@item hostile
Instruct the garrisons to attack the specified unit on sight.  Each
garrison will accept up to three @code{decree hostile} orders per month.
Additional hostile decrees are ignored.

Unlike nobles and players, who can declare themselves hostile to nations
or monsters, garrisons can only be declared hostile against specific
units. 
@end table

@node dedicate, default, decree, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{dedicate}
@cartouche
@example
@code{dedicate} @var{priest}
@bullet{} time: 7 days
@bullet{} priority: 3
@end example
@end cartouche

By use of this command, a noble dedicates himself to a priest (and, by
extension, the priest's god).

Once dedicated, a noble may not change his dedication until the priest
is dead and laid to rest.  Priests may not use this command; they are
already dedicated to their god.  Mages also may not use this command,
since the gods will not accept mages as followers.

The priest and the dedicating noble must be in the same location for the
entire time of the dedication ceremony.

@node default, defend, dedicate, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{default}
@cartouche
@example
@code{default} @var{who}
@bullet{} time: 0 days
@bullet{} priority: 0
@end example
@end cartouche

Clear any @code{hostile}, @code{neutral} or @code{defend} attitude for
the unit or faction.  May be issued by either a noble or the player
entity.

@var{who} may be either a unit id, a nation name, or "monster".

@xref{Declared attitudes} for more information about declared attitudes.

Related orders: @ref{defend} @ref{neutral} @ref{hostile}

@node defend, drop, default, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{defend}
@cartouche
@example
@code{defend} @var{who}
@bullet{} time: 0 days
@bullet{} priority: 0
@end example
@end cartouche

Declare a unit or player to have attitude @code{defend} towards another
unit, nation, or player @var{who}.  When a unit is attacked, other units
which have @code{defend} attitude to the unit will join the combat and
aid with defense.

To declare an attitude toward a nation, use the nation's name (or any
non-ambiguous first part of the name) in the command:

@example
defend Mandor
@end example

Case is ignored.

When a combat occurs, the attitude of the top-most noble in each
stack in the location is checked.  If any unit is declared @code{defend}
to the victim of the attack, the unit's stack will join the combat on
the victim's side.

@var{who} may be either a unit id or a nation name.

To remove a unit from the defend list, set it's attitude to @ref{neutral} or
@ref{default}. 

To remove all units from the defend list (to clear the list), use the
@ref{defend} command with no arguments.

@xref{Declared attitudes} for more information about declared attitudes.

Related orders: @ref{default} @ref{neutral} @ref{hostile}

@node drop, email, defend, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{drop}
@cartouche
@example
@code{drop} @var{item} @var{qty} [@var{have-left}]
@bullet{} time: 0 days
@bullet{} priority: 1
@end example
@end cartouche

Discard the specified quantity of item.  If have-left is specified, at
least this many will not be discarded.  If quantity is zero, the entire
inventory of the given item will be discarded.

@c @group
For example, if Feasel has 100 gold [1]:

@example
@group
drop 1 50          #  Throw away 50 gold
drop 1 0           #  Throw away 100 gold  (0 means all)
drop 1 100         #  Throw away 100 gold
drop 1 100 25      #  Throw away 75 gold   (keep 25)
drop 1 0 25        #  Throw away 75 gold   (keep 25)
@end group
@end example

Common items including gold, lumber, swords, etc. are permanently lost
when discarded.  It is assumed that they are quickly scavenged by
others.

Unique items, such as magical artifacts, scrolls, potions and rare
books, do not become permanently lost.  Such items will be found through
exploration of the province in which they were lost.  Unique items lost
at sea will wash ashore on a nearby island or coast, where they may also
be found through exploration.

@c @group
The @code{drop} order is also be used to release men such as peasants,
workers, soldiers, etc. from service:

@example
@group
drop 10 3               # Release 3 peasants from service
@end group
@end example

When used on a ship, @code{drop} will throw items overboard.

@node email, execute, drop, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{email}
@cartouche
@example
@code{email} @var{new email address}
@end example
@end cartouche

Change the address to which turn results should be sent to the given
address.  Must appear after the @code{begin} order.

To change your email address, send in

@example
@group
begin 999
email new@@address.com   # give your new address
end
@end group
@end example

As a security measure, the confirmation will be sent to both the new and
old addresses.

If you want to send your turn report to two or more addresses, use
both addresses in the email command, separated with a comma:

@example
@group
begin 999
email new@@address.com,other@@address.com
end
@end group
@end example

@node execute, explore, email, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{execute}
@cartouche
@example
@code{execute} [@var{prisoner}]
@bullet{} time: 0 days
@bullet{} priority: 1
@end example
@end cartouche

Put the given prisoner to death.  If no prisoner is specified, all of
the noble's prisoners will be executed.

@node explore, fee, execute, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{explore}
@cartouche
@example
@code{explore}
@bullet{} time: 7 days
@bullet{} priority: 3
@end example
@end cartouche

Explore the current location for hidden features or routes.  If there is
something to find, there is a 33% chance with each attempt that the
explorer will find it.

@example
@group
1: > explore
1: Explore location for hidden features.
  @dots{}
7: Exploration uncovers no new features.
@end group
@end example

Exploration in a province may also turn up rare items which have been
lost.

If the exploring noble is on a ship on the ocean, the surrounding
ocean province will be searched for hidden islands or sea routes.

Priests of Domingo have a 50% chance of success.

@node fee, ferry, explore, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{fee}
@cartouche
@example
@code{fee} weight | men | nobles @var{gold} [@var{where}]
@bullet{} time: 0 days
@bullet{} priority: 1
@end example
@end cartouche

Set a fee required to @code{board} a ship or enter a location.

The first argument to fee is the word "weight", "men" or "nobles".  This
selects whether the fee is per 1000 weight entering, per 100 men
entering, or per noble.  The second argument is the cost:

@example
@group
> fee nobles 5  # charge each noble 5 gold to enter
@end group
@end example

Fees may be charged in combination by using the fee command several
times: 

@example
@group
> fee nobles 5  # charge each noble 5 gold to enter a17.
> fee men 10    # Also charge 10 gold for each 100 men they have.
@end group
@end example

For small locations such as ships, towers, yew groves, and etc., the fee
can only be set by the owner of the location.

For provinces and cities, the fee can only be set by the ruler of the
province or city.  The ruler must have garrisoned the province and be
the owner of the controlling castle.  (For convenience, any noble in the
ruler's faction is permitted to issue the @code{fee} command.)

To set the fee for a province or city, use the optional third argument
to specify where you are setting the fee:

@example
@group
> fee nobles 10 a17  # charge each noble 5 gold to enter a17.
@end group
@end example

Fees for provinces and cities are collected only when a garrison is
present and a noble is sitting in the controlling castle.

New fees do not take affect until the end of the month.  (This prevents
an unscrupulous player from springing a "surprise" fee on you.)  Fees
appear in the turn reports.  Note that if you enter a location sight
unseen, you might be charged an unexpected fee!

To remove the fee from a location, set the fee to zero.  When a "small"
location is vacated, any fee set in that location will be removed.  Fees
in provinces and cities persist until removed.

@node ferry, fish, fee, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{ferry}
@cartouche
@example
@code{ferry}
@bullet{} time: 0 days
@bullet{} priority: 1
@end example
@end cartouche

Sound a ship's horn, signaling units in port waiting with @code{wait
ferry} that they may begin boarding the ferry.  @code{ferry} may only be
used by the captain of a ship.

Units waiting to board a ferry should use @code{wait ferry} instead of
@code{wait ship} to allow existing passengers on the ferry time to
unload.  If those trying to @code{board} do so before existing
passengers have unloaded, the @code{board} order may fail because of
ship weight limits.

@node fish, flag, ferry, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{fish}
@cartouche
@example
@code{fish} [@var{number of fish}] [@var{days}]
@bullet{} time: as given
@bullet{} priority: 3
@end example
@end cartouche

A unit must be on a ship on the ocean in order to fish.  Each day, the
unit has a 50% chance of encountering fish.  If fish are found, each
sailor will catch one fish that day, as long as fish stocks in the ocean
province last.  Ocean provinces generate 50 catchable fish per month.

A unit must know the Fishing [1004] subskill of Shipcraft [1000] in order
to fish, and must have at least one sailor.

Only sailors may be used for fishing.  Pirates will not fish.

@c @group
Examples:

@example
@group
fish         # obtain as many fish as possible
fish 25      # stop after getting 25 fish
fish 0 5     # fish for five days
fish 25 5    # stop after five days, or 25 fish, whichever
             # comes first
@end group
@end example

In all cases, fishing will cease as soon as the stocks in the ocean
province have been exhausted.  @code{fish} is an alias for
@samp{@code{collect} 87}.

@node flag, fly, fish, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{flag}
@cartouche
@example
@code{flag} string
@bullet{} time: 0 days
@bullet{} priority: 1
@end example
@end cartouche

Signal nobles waiting with a @code{wait flag} order.  The string is
an arbitrary sequence of nobles or numbers, but it should match the
flag specified in the @code{wait flag} order.

@c @group
For example, a noble may wait for a particular signal from
Osswid [5499]:

@example
@group
> wait flag yellow 5499
@end group
@end example

@c @group
This will wait for Osswid [5499] to raise a flag saying @samp{yellow}.
Osswid would issue:

@example
@group
> flag yellow
@end group
@end example

Which would cause the wait order to complete.

@c @group
The @code{wait flag} order defaults to watching for flags from units in
the player's faction.  It may also watch for flags from units in another
faction, a flag from a specific unit, or a flag from any unit in the
game:

@example
@group
wait flag yellow        # wait for 'flag yellow' from a unit
                        # in our faction

wait flag yellow 5499   # wait for 5499 to order 'flag yellow'

wait flag yellow 918    # wait for any unit belonging to player
                        # 918 to order 'flag yellow'.

wait flag yellow 0      # wait for any unit in the game to give
                        # the yellow flag
@end group
@end example

Nobles do not need to be in the same location to flag.

Flags are remembered for the duration of the month.  If a @code{wait
flag} is issued for a flag which has already been raised, the wait will
immediately finish (it will take zero time).

However, flags which have been raised are not remembered between turns,
so a flag raised on the 30th of month 5 will not satisfy a @code{wait
flag} on the 1st of month 6.

@node fly, forget, flag, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{fly}
@cartouche
@example
@code{fly} @var{direction or destination} [@dots{}]
@bullet{} time: varies
@bullet{} priority: 2
@end example
@end cartouche

Fly in the indicated direction, or to the specified location.  Refer to
the @code{move} order for details about movement.

Nobles must have some means of flight to be able to use @code{fly}.
For instance, a sufficient number of winged horses must be available to
carry the entire stack and its belongings.  If the weight of the stack
exceeds the flight weight capacity, the @code{fly} order will fail.

Flying traverses any link in a maximum of three days.

@example
@group
rated time      time to fly
 of route         across
----------      -----------
0 days          0 days
1 day           1 day
3 days          3 days
4 days          3 days
8 days          3 days
@end group
@end example

All flying stacks (e.g., winged horses, angels, etc.) become tired when
flying over the ocean, as they have no place to land and rest.  Up to
fifteen days may be spent flying over the ocean.  At the end of the
fifteenth day, the exhausted stack will be unable to continue, and the
entire stack will plunge into the sea, killing all of the stack's
nobles.

Any arrival at a land or ship location will allow the flying creatures
to rest and regain their strength.

Multiple destinations or destinations may be given as arguments to
@code{fly}.  If the first fails, the next will be tried, until a
passable route is found, or @code{fly} runs out of arguments.

For example, @samp{@code{fly} n e w} would first try to fly north.  If travel
north was not possible for any reason, east would next be tried, then
west.  In this way exploring units can attempt to deal with the case of
running into a hole in the map or other impassable province.

@node forget, form, fly, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{forget}
@cartouche
@example
@code{forget} @var{skill}
@bullet{} time: 0 days
@bullet{} priority: 1
@end example
@end cartouche

Forget all knowledge of a skill.  If a category skill is specified, all
subskills within the category will also be forgotten.  You *never*
recover any NPs (or gold) you might have spent to learn a skill when you
forget it.

In some cases, effects from learned skills persist even after you've
forgotten the skill.  For example, if you use [1102] Fight to the Death
to set your breakpoint to 0%, that breakpoint may remain even after you
forget that skill.

@node form, format, forget, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{form}
@cartouche
@example
@code{form} @var{unit} "@var{name of new noble}"
@bullet{} time: 7 days
@bullet{} priority: 3
@end example
@end cartouche

Spend a Noble Point to obtain a new noble for the player's faction.
Nobles must be formed in a city.  Note that if you're in a tower (or in
a castle, a guild, a temple, etc.) in a city, form will fail.  You must
be directly in the city.

@c @group
The @var{unit} parameter should be selected from the line near the top
of the turn report listing new noble numbers:

@example
@group
The next five nobles formed will be:  5717 3215 4902 4489 5628
@end group
@end example

If 0 is given for @var{unit}, the first number in the list will be
chosen.  However, if more than one @code{form} is to be issued during
the month, it can be uncertain which will execute first.  By specifying
the new unit number, the player will know the correct entity number when
submitting orders for the new noble.

Any noble in the player's faction may issue @code{form}.  The newly
obtained noble will appear and stack beneath the forming noble.  The
new noble is given the name specified as the second argument to
@code{form}.

Orders for new units may be submitted in the turn they are formed.  As
soon as the new unit comes into existence, it will begin to execute its
commands.

New units are unequipped and untrained, and join with loyalty contract-500.

@c @group
Example:

@example
@group
1: > form 3215 "Feasel the Wicked"
1: Attempt to form a new noble.
7: Feasel the Wicked [3215] stacks beneath us.
@end group
@end example

More than five units may not be formed in a turn.

@node format, garrison, form, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{format}
@cartouche
@example
@code{format} [CLEAR] [HTML] [TEXT] [RAW] [TAGS] [ALT] [PATH http://...]
@end example
@end cartouche

The format command is used to set the format of the turn report.

Four basic turn report formats are available:

The RAW format produces "raw" output.  Raw output is largely unformatted
and contains both the embedded tags and all of the text output.  The raw
format is useful mainly to players who want to post-process their turns
themselves, e.g., to produce their own version of HTML output.  For
details on the raw format, see @ref{Appendix - Output Formats}.

The TEXT format produces a text-only turn report.

The HTML format produces a turn report suitable for viewing with a Web
browser.

Specifying the TAGS format embeds Age of God tags into your turn report.
These tags can be used to automatically process the turn report, e.g.,
to extract location information for a map database.  For details on the
format of tags, see @ref{Appendix - Output Formats}.

You may select the format of your turn report by using the format
command followed by one or more of the HTML, TEXT, or RAW keywords.  You
may set multiple formats (e.g., HTML and RAW).  In this case, you will
be sent multiple turn reports, one in each format you've selected.  The
turn reports will contain a keyword in the subject line of the email
indicating the format (so that you can automatically sort them).

To reset your format choices, use "FORMAT CLEAR".  This will clear all
formats.  (If you do not select a format, you will receive only a text
format turn report.)

Some players find the location activity logs less useful than others,
and prefer them to be banished to the end of the turn report.  The
command "FORMAT ALT" will do this.  This alternate format is also
cleared by the "FORMAT CLEAR" command.

@table @asis
@item 0
Noble reports listed first, followed by location reports including
activity logs.

@item 1
Location reports without activity logs, followed by noble reports,
followed by location activity logs.
@end table

Finally, you may use the format command to set an initial path for the
external links in your HTML format turn report.

In the HTML turn report format, any noble, location or item that does
not appear in your turn report is linked to an HTML page of the same
name.  For example, a noble "John Hawkins [ag7]" will be linked to
"http:ag7.html".  If you create a web page "ag7.html" in the directory
where you keep your turn reports, then clicking on the name "John
Hawkins [ag7]" will link you to that web page (where you could, for
example, store information about him).

However, you might want that link to point to some other location.  For
instance, you might be part of an alliance that keeps all information on
a central server.  In that case, you can use the "FORMAT PATH" command
to make the link point to that server.  For example, if you give the
command "FORMAT PATH http://home.me.org/tag/", then "John Hawkins [ag7]"
will be linked to "http://home.me.org/tag/ag7.html".

To clear the path, use "FORMAT PATH".

@node garrison, get, format, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{garrison}
@cartouche
@example
@code{garrison} @var{castle}
@bullet{} time: 1 day
@bullet{} priority: 3
@end example
@end cartouche

Claim a province in the name of a castle by leaving a garrison of
soldiers to defend it.

The castle must be completed in order to bind a garrison to it.

There may not be any existing garrison in the location.  Only provinces
may be garrisoned (the noble should be at the outermost level, not
inside a sublocation or building).

The noble must have ten soldiers [12] to create a garrison.  The
soldiers will be removed from the noble's inventory and placed in the
new garrison.

@xref{Garrisons} for details about how garrisons work.

@node get, give, garrison, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{get}
@cartouche
@example
@code{get} @var{who} @var{item} [@var{qty}] [@var{have-left}]
@bullet{} time: 0 days
@bullet{} priority: 1
@end example
@end cartouche

Get the given quantity of item from the specified target.

Nobles may @code{get} items from other units in their faction, or
from garrisons which they control.  @code{get} may not be used to take
items from another faction's units; the other faction's units must issue
@code{give} orders.

Specifying zero for the quantity will cause the unit to attempt to take
all of the target's inventory of the item.  If have-left is given, at
least that many will not be taken.

@c @group
For example, if Feasel [5499] had 100 gold[1]:

@example
@group
get 5499 1 50          #  Get 50 gold from Feasel
get 5499 1 0           #  Get all 100 gold from Feasel
get 5499 1 100         #  Get all 100 gold from Feasel
get 5499 1 100 25      #  Get 75 gold from Feasel
get 5499 1 0 25        #  Get 75 gold from Feasel
@end group
@end example

@c @group
Prisoners may also be transferred with the @code{get} order.

@example
@group
get 5499 4569          #  Transfer prisoner [4569] from [5499]
@end group
@end example

When taking men from a garrison, the garrison must be left with at least
ten men, or the @code{get} will fail.  For example, if a garrison had
five peasants and six soldiers, either a peasant or a soldier could be
taken.  No men can be taken from a garrison with less than ten men.

@node give, guard, get, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{give}
@cartouche
@example
@code{give} @var{to-who} @var{item} [@var{qty}] [@var{have-left}]
@bullet{} time: 0 days
@bullet{} priority: 1
@end example
@end cartouche

Give quantity of an item in inventory to another noble.  Specifying
zero for quantity will cause the unit to give all of its inventory of
the item.  An amount specified by have-left will be retained.

@c @group
For example, if Feasel has 100 gold [1]:

@example
@group
give 5499 1 50          #  Give 50 gold to [5499]
give 5499 1 0           #  Give all 100 gold to [5499]
give 5499 1 100         #  Give all 100 gold to [5499]
give 5499 1 100 25      #  Give 75 gold to [5499]
give 5499 1 0 25        #  Give 75 gold to [5499]
@end group
@end example

@c @group
Prisoners may also be transferred with the @code{give} order.

@example
@group
give 5499 4569          #  Give prisoner [4569] to [5499]
@end group
@end example

If you give something to a noble from another faction, that noble must
use the @code{accept} command or the gift will be refused.  See
@ref{accept}. 

In some games, players may put gold into their claim.  To do this, have
your noble give the gold to your faction id.  For example, if you are
faction [x8x], then

@example
@group
> give x8x 1 100
@end group
@end example

There is a 10% fee collected when placing gold into claim, so in this
case the actual deposit would only be 90 gold.

@node guard, guild, give, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{guard}
@cartouche
@example
@code{guard} @var{flag}
@bullet{} time: 0 days
@bullet{} priority: 1
@end example
@end cartouche

Protect a city or province from looting and pillaging.
@samp{@code{guard} 1} will cause the unit to suppress @code{pillage}
attempts by other nobles.  The guarding unit must be the top unit in its
stack.

Any number of units in a location may be on guard.  The message @samp{on
guard} will appear next to guard units in the location report.

A noble attempting to pillage the city or province may specify a
flag which causes them to attack the guards.  In this case, all of the
stacks on guard will respond to the attack.  However, allies of the
guard units will not respond.  Only guard stacks will be involved in
combat to suppress looting and pillaging.

Specifying a flag of 0 turns off guarding.  Any movement by the guarding
noble will also clear the guard flag.  For example, if a unit issued
@samp{@code{guard} 1} in a city, then moved out of the city, the @code{guard}
flag would be cleared, and the unit would no longer be on guard.

The guarding units must be inside they location they are to guard.
Units in a castle in a city will not protect the city.  Units guarding a
city will not protect the surrounding province.

Note that a guarding unit will not come to the defense of a garrison if
it is directly attacked.  To help defend a garrison, use the
@ref{defend} command.

@node guild, honor, guard, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{guild}
@cartouche
@example
@code{guild} @var{skill school}
@bullet{} time: 7 days
@bullet{} priority: 3
@bullet{} cost: 250 gold
@end example
@end cartouche

From inside a tower, convert it to a guild hall for the indicated skill
school (see @ref{Guild Halls}).  To use this command the noble must be
the only occupant of the tower.

To create a guild hall, a noble must either (1) already be a member of
the guild for the indicated skill school, or (2) be ready to join that
guild (i.e., must know all the non-guild skills of that skill school).
Creating a guild hall causes the creator to join the appropriate guild.

Guilds must be created in cities, and only one guild of a type is
allowed in a city.

@node honor, hostile, guild, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{honor}
@cartouche
@example
@code{honor} @var{amount}
@bullet{} time: 0 days
@bullet{} priority: 3
@end example
@end cartouche

Pay a unit for its service.  Units paid will take gold out of their own
inventory and use it for their own purposes.

Nobles with oathbound loyalty will refuse to be paid, and reject the
gold.  Nobles with fear loyalty will be converted to contract loyalty.

The amount of money paid accumulates in the noble's contract loyalty
rating.  For instance, a fear-10 noble honored with 500 gold would have
loyalty contract-500.  A contract-250 noble honored with 500 gold would
become contract-750.

@node hostile, identify, honor, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{hostile}
@cartouche
@example
@code{hostile} @var{who}
@bullet{} time: 0 days
@bullet{} priority: 0
@end example
@end cartouche

Declare unit, nation or player @var{who} hostile to the unit or player
issuing the order.  Units declared hostile will be attacked on sight.
Players may also specify "hostile monster" which will cause all monsters
to be attacked on sight.

To declare an attitude toward a nation, use the nation's name (or any
non-ambiguous first part of the name) in the command:

@example
hostile Mandor
@end example

Case is ignored.

If the player entity issues @code{hostile}, any unit in the player's
faction will attack the hostile unit on sight.  If an individual
noble issues @code{hostile}, the noble will attack the hostile
unit on sight.

Units will only initiate automatic attacks if they are in perfect
health.  Hostile units which are being held prisoner will not be
attacked.  Automatic attacks take place at priority 3 (the same as
@ref{attack}). 

An entire faction may be declared hostile by specifying another player
entity instead of an individual unit.  Any unit not concealing its
affiliation with the faction declared hostile would be attacked on
sight.

@c @group
Examples:

@example
@group
hostile 4240            # attack 4240 on sight
hostile 778             # attack any member of faction 778 on sight
@end group
@end example

To remove a unit from the hostile list, set it's attitude to @ref{neutral} or
@ref{default}. 

To remove all units from the hostile list (to clear the list), use the
@ref{hostile} command with no arguments.

@xref{Declared attitudes} for more information about declared attitudes.

Related orders: @ref{default} @ref{defend} @ref{neutral}

@node identify, make, hostile, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{identify}
@cartouche
@example
@code{identify} @var{item id}
@bullet{} time: 0 days
@bullet{} priority: 3
@end example
@end cartouche

The identify command causes a noble to closely examine an item for the
tiny, cryptic runes that indicate the purpose of the ancient magical
artifacts that can sometimes be found in Olympia (see @ref{Appendix - Magical
Artifacts}).  If the runes can be found and read, the identify command
will display the item's enchantment, e.g., 

@example
8: > identify atq
8: You carefully read the runes on this artifact and identify it as:
8: Reduced Maintenance, 9%.
@end example

Some magical artifacts will have no enchantment, while others will be
missing runes, and so cannot be identified, e.g., 

@example
8: > identify cz0
8: You carefully read the runes on this artifact and identify it as:
8: no enchantment.
8: > identify atq
8: You are unable to identify that item.
@end example

Note that @code{identify} does not change the name of the artifact.  You
can change the name of the artifact using the @ref{name} command, if
you'd like.  Keep in mind that someone scrying your noble will see that
new name!

@node make, message, identify, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{make}
@cartouche
@example
@code{make} @var{item} [@var{qty}]
@bullet{} time: as given
@bullet{} priority: 3
@end example
@end cartouche

@c @group
Make the indicated item.  @var{qty} defaults to as many as possible.
Each of the following items requires one day each to produce:

@example
@group
num   item           skill    material
---   ----           -----    --------
 40   hvy. crossbow  1106     wood [77] & iron [79]
 72   longbow        1106     yew [68]
 73   plate armor    1106     iron [79]
 74   longsword      1106     iron [79]
 75   pike           1106     wood [77]
 80   leather        none     ox [76]
 84   blank scroll   1500     lana bark [64]
 85   crossbow       1106     wood [77]
 94   woven basket   none     none
 95   clay pot       none     none
@end group
@end example

Knowledge of Weaponsmithing [1106], a subskill of Combat [1100], is
required to make weapons and armor.  Alchemy [1500] must be known to
produce blank scrolls from lana bark.  No skills or input materials are
needed to make woven baskets or clay pots.

@c @group
Examples:

To make 5 longbows from 5 yew (a kind of wood):

@example
@group
make 72 5               # takes 5 days
@end group
@end example

@c @group
To make 1 plate armor from 1 iron:

@example
@group
make 73 1               # takes 1 day
@end group
@end example

@c @group
To make 5 woven baskets:

@example
@group
make 94 5               # takes 5 days
@end group
@end example

Although making pots and baskets is considered menial labor, some
desperate nobles have resorted to selling them in cities to earn gold.
Each city in Olympia either buys woven baskets or clay pots.

@node message, move, make, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{message}
@cartouche
@example
@code{message} @var{# of lines of text} @var{to-who}
@bullet{} time: 1 day
@bullet{} priority: 3
@end example
@end cartouche

Send a message to the target named in the second parameter.  The target
may be any valid entity, such as a noble, a player, or a location
(including provinces, cities, ships, buildings, or other sublocations).

The number of lines in the message should be given as the first argument
to @code{message}.  The text of the message should follow the
@code{message} order.

@c @group
For example:

@example
@group
message 2 2909
  Aye, ye not be safe in this world for long, Oleg.
  I be remembering ya, and yer past fould deeds.  Arrr!
move ev18
recruit
@end group
@end example

(The text of the message is indented here to make the orders easier
to read.  The order scanner will ignore leading spaces on each line.)

@c @group
This would send the message to noble [2909].  The recipient would
see the message in his turn report:

@example
@group
Received a message from Captain McCook [2104]:
   "Aye, ye not be safe for long in this world, Oleg.
I be remembering ya, and yer past foul deeds.  Arrr!"
@end group
@end example

Take care to carefully count the lines of text in the message.  If the
wrong number of lines is given, your noble may end up sending his
orders to the recipient instead of executing them.

Each line of message text must be less than 60 characters long, or the
message will be rejected.

@node move, maxpay, message, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{move}
@cartouche
@example
@code{move} @var{direction or destination} [@dots{}]
@bullet{} time: varies
@bullet{} priority: 2
@end example
@end cartouche

Travel in the indicated direction, or to the specified location.  If a
location is specified, there must be a direct route to it from the
noble's current location.

Compass points may be abbreviated: @samp{n}, @samp{s}, @samp{e},
@samp{w}.  Units may also @code{move out} of a sublocation to the
surrounding province or location, or @code{move in} to a sublocation
from the surrounding province or location.  Note that @code{move in} is
ambiguous if there are two sublocations (e.g., a sacred grove and a
temple).  In that case you should move to the id of the sublocation you
want, so that you don't end up someplace unexpected (e.g., in the sacred
grove when you expected to be in the temple).

Units may also @code{move up} and @code{move down} to go up and down.
Currently this is only useful when moving up and down through the levels
of a mine.

Visible routes leaving each province are listed in the turn report.

@c @group
For example:

@example
@group
Routes leaving Plain [cw04]:
   North, to Ocean [cv04], South Sea, 1 day
   East, to Plain [cw05], 7 days
   South, to Plain [cx04], 7 days
   West, to Plain [cw03], 7 days
@end group
@end example

@c @group
The following would be valid move commands from the example
province:

@example
@group
move e  -or-  move cw05  -or-  move east
move s  -or-  move cx04  -or-  move south
move w  -or-  move cw03  -or-  move west
@end group
@end example

Note that @code{move} cannot be used to enter the ocean region [cv04].
The noble would need to issue the @code{sail} order as captain of a
ship to move north into the South Sea.

Route distances are rated in the number of days it would normally take a
lightly loaded noble, walking, to traverse them.  Actual travel
times may differ from the rated times.

Nobles overloaded with belongings will make slower progress.  Horses
usually speed progress, but over especially rough or treacherous
terrain, they may actually slow travel because they must be led and
managed.

Inventory is considered for the stack as a whole.  For instance, if one
noble possesses enough horses for every member of the stack, the
stack may ride.  Similarly, if one noble is badly overloaded, but
other nobles have extra carrying capacity, they will assist their
stackmate.  Distribution of goods between units within a stack is
irrelevant to movement.

The units stacked beneath a moving noble will move with the stack
leader.  If the unit issuing @code{move} is stacked beneath another
noble, he will first automatically unstack before movement begins.

@c @group
For example:

@example
@group
Seen here:
   Osswid the Constructor [5499], accompanied by:
      Feasel the Wicked [502]
@end group
@end example

If Osswid issues a @code{move} order, Feasel will go with Osswid.  If
Feasel issues a @code{move} order, however, Feasel would first unstack
from Osswid before beginning travel.

Multiple destinations or directions may be given as arguments to
the @code{move} order.  If the first fails, the next will be tried, until
a passable route is found, or @code{move} runs out of arguments.

For example, @samp{@code{move} n e w} would first try to move north.  If travel
north was not possible for any reason, east would next be tried, then
west.  In this way exploring units can attempt to deal with the case of
running into an impassable province or a coast.

Some locations may charge noble to enter.  See @ref{Entrance Fees}.

The size of the entrance to some locations is limited, and only stacks
of that size or smaller may enter (or attack) that location.  For
example:

@example
Inner locations:
   Lair [ad7n], lair, 1 day, entrance size: 4, owner:
      Harpie [jn7t], harpies, number: 12
@end example

Lair [ad7n] can only be entered -- or attacked -- by stacks of size four
or less.  (If you attack with more than that number in your stack, the
attack will immediately fail.)  Notice that this does not restrict the
size of stacks inside the location, only the number that may enter at
one time.

Some locations may not permit a noble to enter.  For example, a province
guarded by a garrison may close its border, refusing admission to nobles
not on the ruler's admission list.  In this case, the @code{move} order
will fail in zero time.

To enter a closed location, a noble should use the @code{attack} order.
It is sometimes convenient to use @code{move} and @code{attack} in
combination, to ensure entry to a location.  For example, if Feasel gave
the commands:

@example
@group
move cw05
attack cw05
@end group
@end example

he would first try to move into cw05.  If that succeeds, the subsequent
attack command will fail (since Feasel will already be in cw05).  If the
move fails because the border is closed, the attack will happen.  If the
move fails for some other reason (such as the location not existing)
then the attack will fail as well. 

A moving stack does not leave its current location until the day it
completes the move.  This means that the stack can be attacked until its
move completes, e.g., on an eight day move the stack could be attacked
for eight days after it begins the move.

@node maxpay, name, move, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{maxpay}
@cartouche
@example
@code{maxpay} [@var{gold}]
@bullet{} time: 0 days
@bullet{} priority: 1
@end example
@end cartouche

Sets the maximum amount a unit will pay to enter a location (see
@xref{fee}).  If set to zero, a unit will refuse to enter any location
charging a fee.

The default is a maxpay of zero (pay nothing).

@node name, neutral, maxpay, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{name}
@cartouche
@example
@code{name} [@var{unit}] "@var{new name for unit}"
@bullet{} time: 0 days
@bullet{} priority: 1
@end example
@end cartouche

Change the name of an item or unit.  If a unit number is specified, the
given unit's name will be changed.  This is useful for setting the name
on entities which don't execute orders directly, such as ships and
castles.  Names may not be set for units controlled by another player.

Names of nobles should be no longer than 35 characters.  Names for
other entities, such as towers, ships and items should be no longer than
25 characters.  Longer names will be rejected.

Note that the name must be enclosed in quotes or it will not be
recognized.

@c @group
Examples:

@example
@group
> name "Feasel the Wicked"
> name cx53 "Castle Chardia"
@end group
@end example

@node neutral, notab, name, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{neutral}
@cartouche
@example
@code{neutral} @var{who}
@bullet{} time: 0 days
@bullet{} priority: 0
@end example
@end cartouche

Declare unit, nation or player @var{who} to have attitude @code{neutral}
to the player or faction issuing the order.  Units declared neutral will
not be aided if they are attacked.  Players may also specify "neutral
monster".

To declare an attitude toward a nation, use the nation's name (or any
non-ambiguous first part of the name) in the command:

@example
neutral Mandor
@end example

Case is ignored.

Units in the same faction will defend each other if they are attacked,
unless either unit is concealing its lord.  This behavior may be
suppressed with @code{neutral}.  A unit may declare other units in its
faction neutral.  Or, the entire faction may declare itself neutral.  In
this case, members of the faction who were attacked would not aid each
other, unless they were stacked together.

To remove a unit from the default list, set it's attitude to
@ref{neutral}.

To remove all units from the default list (to clear the list), use the
@ref{default} command with no arguments.

@xref{Declared attitudes} for more information about declared attitudes.

Related orders: @ref{default} @ref{defend} @ref{hostile}

@node notab, oath, neutral, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{notab}
@cartouche
@example
@code{notab} @var{num}
@end example
@end cartouche

@c @group
Ordinarily, @code{tab} characters may appear in turn reports.  Some
players read their reports on computer equipment which cannot correctly
display @code{tab} characters.  If this is the case, issue the command:

@example
@group
notab 1
@end group
@end example

and tabs will be converted to spaces for your report.

@node oath, password, notab, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{oath}
@cartouche
@example
@code{oath} @var{level}
@bullet{} time: 1 day
@bullet{} priority: 3
@end example
@end cartouche

Have a noble take an oath of loyalty.  Either 1 or 2 should be
specified for @var{level}.  One or two NPs will be deducted from the
player's faction, and the specified noble's loyalty will become
oath-1 or oath-2.

Noble Points spent on oathbound loyalty accumulate.  Thus, oath-1 may
be upgraded to oath-2 with the @samp{@code{oath} 1} order.

@node password, pay, oath, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{password}
@cartouche
@example
@code{password} ["@var{password}"]
@end example
@end cartouche

Set or clear a password for the player.  If no argument is given, any
existing password will be cleared.  Otherwise, the specified password
will be set.

@c @group
Examples:

@example
@group
begin 663
password "xyzzy9"
end
@end group
@end example

@c @group
This would set a password @samp{xyzzy9} for the faction.  Further orders
will require the password to be specified after the player number on the
@code{begin} line:

@example
@group
begin 663 "xyzzy9"
password                # clear the password
end
@end group
@end example

IMPORTANT: Don't share your password with anyone.  If you do, they can
send in orders for you and see all your turn reports for all your games! 

@node pay, pillage, password, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{pay}
@cartouche
@example
@code{pay} @var{to-who} [@var{amount}] [@var{have-left}]
@bullet{} time: 0 days
@bullet{} priority: 1
@end example
@end cartouche

Pay amount of gold to indicated entity, keeping at least have-left funds
available.  The @code{pay} command is shorthand for the equivalent
@code{give} command to transfer gold from one unit to another.

The amount of gold to be paid will default to all of the unit's gold if
not specified or if zero.

@c @group
For example, if Feasel has 100 gold:

@example
@group
pay 5499 100            # pay 100 to [5499]
pay 5499 0              # pay 100 to [5499]
pay 5499 0 25           # pay 75 to [5499]
pay 5499 100 25         # pay 75 to [5499]
@end group
@end example


@node pillage, players, pay, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{pillage}
@cartouche
@example
@code{pillage} [@var{flag}]
@bullet{} time: 7 days
@bullet{} priority: 3
@end example
@end cartouche

Loot and pillage a province or city.  If flag is not given, pillaging
will not take place if the province is being protected by guards.  If
flag is 1, the looters will first attack the guards, then proceed with
pillaging if the guards are defeated.

At least 10 fighters must be in the pillaging stack.  Pillaging may be
done with beasts or men, but the noble directing the pillaging must be
able to control the pillagers in battle.  Only the top most noble in a
stack may initiate pillaging; only the men he directly controls are
involved in the pillaging.  Other nobles in his stack will continue with
whatever actions they are doing.

Pillaging kills one peasant for every two fighters pillaging until there
are 100 or less peasants left in a province.  It then becomes more
difficult to find the peasants, and five fighters are required to find
and kill each peasant.  Each peasant kill yields 2 gold.  For example, a
location with 112 peasants pillaged by a group of 218 men would kill 51
peasants and yield (at most) 102 gold.  If the peasants do not have the
gold to pay off the pillages (e.g., they have paid it in taxes) then the
pillagers may collect less than the maximum gold (or none at all).

Pillaging can be dangerous.  There is a 33% chance that a mob of 12-36
angry peasants will form to resist further pillaging attempts.  Angry
peasants have a combat rating of (attack-2, defense-1, missile-0).  If a
mob forms, there is a 33% chance that the mob will immediately attack
the pillager in retaliation.

@node players, post, pillage, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{players}
@cartouche
@example
@code{players}
@end example
@end cartouche

Ask the order scanner to send a list of the players in the game.

@node post, press, players, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{post}
@cartouche
@example
@code{post} @var{# of lines of following text}
@bullet{} time: 1 day
@bullet{} priority: 3
@end example
@end cartouche

Post a public message in the location.  All nobles in the location
will see the text of the message in the location description section of
their turn reports.  Signs remain visible for one turn.

@c @group
The number of lines in the post should be given as an argument to
@code{post}, followed by the text of the sign.  For example, here is a
post command followed by a move and a recruit:

@example
@group
post 3
  All ye beware!  These lands are the property of
  noble Osswid.  Those who trespass here without
  his permission will come to a GRAVE end!
move ev18
recruit
@end group
@end example

(The text of the post is indented here to make the orders easier to
read.  The order scanner will ignore leading spaces on each line.)

Take care to carefully count the lines of text in the post.  If the
wrong number of lines is given, your noble may end up posting his
orders instead of executing them.

Each line of posted text must be less than 60 characters long, or the
post will be rejected.

@node press, practice, post, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{press}
@cartouche
@example
@code{press} @var{# of lines of text}
@bullet{} time: 0 days
@bullet{} priority: 1
@end example
@end cartouche

Submit a signed message to the Game Newsletter.

The @code{press} order may be given by a noble or by the player entity.
The identity of the submitting faction will appear in the newsletter.

The number of lines in the entry should be given as an argument to
@code{press}, followed by the text of the entry.  For example, here is a
press item submitted by Osswid [xt8].

@example
@group
PRESS 3
  All ye beware!  Osswid hereby claims the entire continent
  of Provinia as his rightful domain.  Those who trespass here
  without his permission will come to a GRAVE end!
@end group
@end example

Take care to carefully count the lines of text in the post.  If the
wrong number of lines is given, your noble may end up posting
his orders instead of executing them.

Alternatively, one may specify 0 for the lines of text argument,
and terminate the message with the @code{end} keyword:

@example
@group
PRESS 0
  All ye beware!  Osswid hereby claims the entire continent
  of Provinia as his rightful domain.  Those who trespass here
  without his permission will come to a GRAVE end!
END
@end group
@end example

Take great care when using the 0 lines/@code{end} keyword feature.  If you
forget the @code{end}, or mistype it, none of the orders following the
@code{press} command will execute.  Instead, they will be published in the
newsletter.  This is obviously very bad, so if you intend to use the
@code{end} keyword to avoid having to count lines, please be careful.

Each line of posted text must be less than 78 characters long, or
the post will be rejected.

Editorial guidelines for submissions to the Game Newsletter:

@enumerate
@item
No profanity.

@item
No personal insults to other humans (in-character
roleplaying insults are fine).
@end enumerate

In some cases, the Times pays money for submissions.  If so, it will be
noted in the Game description.

@node  practice, promote, press, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{practice}
@cartouche
@example
@code{practice} @var{skill}
@bullet{} time: varies
@bullet{} priority: 3
@bullet{} cost: varies
@end example
@end cartouche

Some skills may be improved with practice.  See @ref{Appendix - Skill 
Dictionary} for the skills that can be improved with practice.
Skills that can be practiced list the number of days of continuous
practice required to raise the skill one experience level and the cost
of practicing the skill.

There is no credit for "partial practice" if practice is interrupted with
the STOP command.

@node promote, quarry, practice, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{promote}
@cartouche
@example
@code{promote} @var{who}
@bullet{} time: 0 days
@bullet{} priority: 1
@end example
@end cartouche

Advance the given unit so that it appears before the noble issuing
@code{promote} in the location list.

The noble to be promoted should be stacked immediately beneath the
promoting noble, or appear later in the location list at the same
level.

@c @group
Examples:

Before:

@example
@group
Osswid the Constructor [5499], accompanied by:
   Feasel the Wicked [502]
@end group
@end example

Osswid issues @samp{@code{promote} 502}:

@example
@group
Feasel the Wicked [502]
Osswid the Constructor [5499]
@end group
@end example

@c @group
Before:

@example
@group
Osswid the Constructor [5499], accompanied by:
   Feasel the Wicked [502]
Candide [1269]
@end group
@end example

Osswid issues @samp{@code{promote} 1269}:

@example
@group
Candide [1269]
Osswid the Constructor [5499], accompanied by:
   Feasel the Wicked [502]
@end group
@end example

A common mistake is to think that @code{promote} can be used to swap the
stack leader and someone in the stack.  For example, if you have 

@example
@group
Osswid the Constructor [5499], accompanied by:
   Feasel the Wicked [502]
@end group
@end example

and Osswid issues @samp{@code{promote} 502}, you do NOT get this:

@example
@group
Feasel the Wicked [502] accompanied by:
   Osswid the Constructor [5499]
@end group
@end example

instead you get two separate stacks, with the Feasel stack ahead of the
Osswid stack in the location report:

@example
@group
Feasel the Wicked [502]
Osswid the Constructor [5499]
@end group
@end example

To swap stack leaders, you need some combination of @ref{stack} and
@ref{unstack} commands.

@node quarry, quit, promote, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{quarry}
@cartouche
@example
@code{quarry} [@var{number of stones}] [@var{days}]
@bullet{} time: as given
@bullet{} priority: 3
@end example
@end cartouche

Building stone is used in the construction of temples, castles and
towers.  Up to 50 stone may be removed from mountain provinces each
month.  Ten stone may be taken from desert provinces or rocky hills each
month.

A unit must have the Stone quarrying [1402] subskill of Construction
[1400] in order to cut building stone.  At least one worker is also
required.

Each worker will cut and prepare one building stone [78] per day.

@c @group
Examples:

@example
@group
quarry         # cut as much building stone as possible
quarry 25      # stop after cutting 25 stone
quarry 0 5     # quarry stone for five days
quarry 25 5    # stop after five days, or 25 stone, whichever
               # comes first
@end group
@end example

In all cases, quarrying will cease as soon as the supply of ready stone
in the province has been exhausted.

@node quit, raze, quarry, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{quit}
@cartouche
@example
@code{quit}
@end example
@end cartouche

Quit Olympia.  This command must be issued by the player entity.

No turn report is mailed for the turn a @code{quit} order is processed.

@node raze, recruit, quit, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{raze}
@cartouche
@example
@code{raze} [@var{target}] [@var{days}]
@bullet{} time: varies
@bullet{} priority: 3
@end example
@end cartouche

Tear down a building.  The command completes when the structure has been
completely destroyed, or when @var{days} have elapsed.  Note that you
must specify @var{target} to specify @var{days}.

A building may be razed from the inside or the outside.  If razed from
the outside, a building must be unoccupied.  The argument @var{target},
if present, is the building to be razed.

If razed from the inside, the razing unit must be the owner of the
structure (the top-most unit inside the building).  The noble will
safely leave the building before it collapses.

@c @group
Sturdier structures require more men to do a given amount of damage:

@example
@group
                 man-days per
structure       point of damage
---------       ---------------
ship                 1
temple               2
inn                  2
tower                2
mine                 2
castle               3
@end group
@end example

For example, two men can cause 1% of damage to a tower in a day.

Only men in the noble's inventory will help with destruction.  The noble is
counted when the number of men are computed.  The noble does not have to
be the stack leader to raze; it's possible for two nobles in the same
stack to be razing different buildings at the same time.

@node recruit, repair, raze, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{recruit}
@cartouche
@example
@code{recruit} [@var{days}]
@bullet{} time: as given
@bullet{} priority: 3
@end example
@end cartouche

Recruit one peasant each day for the given number of days.  If days is
not specified, recruiting will obtain as many peasants as possible.

Peasants may be recruited in any province with more than 100 peasants or
any city or city province with more than 1000 peasants.  Recruiting can
not be done in other sublocations (such as rocky hills, forest glades,
etc.)

Up to 5% of a province's population may be recruited each month.  One
peasant is recruited each day the @code{recruit} command is used.

The @code{recruit} order will stop or fail when no further peasants are
available to be recruited.

For example, one player could recruit for up to 10 days per month in a
mountain province with 200 peasants, obtaining one peasant on each of
the 10 days.

If two players in the province each issued @code{recruit} 10, both would
recruit five peasants (each player would get a peasant a day until all
10 had been recruited).

Recruit is an alias for @samp{@code{collect} 10}.

@node repair, resend, recruit, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{repair}
@cartouche
@example
@code{repair} [@var{days}]
@bullet{} time: as given
@bullet{} priority: 3
@end example
@end cartouche

Repair the damaged ship or building that the noble is inside.
Requires at least one worker [11].

@example
@group
                worker-days per
structure       point of damage
---------       ---------------
ship                 1
temple               2
inn                  2
tower                2
mine                 2
castle               3
@end group
@end example

Work proceeds until the structure has been fully repaired, or the given
number of days has passed.  Multiple units may work at repair simultaneously.

For example, a tower with 50% damage would require 100 worker-days to fully
repair.  A ship with 50% damage would require 50 worker-days.  A castle, 150
worker-days.

Each use of @code{repair} on a ship requires one unit of pitch [261].
One unit of pitch is sufficient for a ship repair job, no matter how
many days the repair takes.  Pitch may be purchased in any port city.

@node resend, rumor, repair, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{resend}
@cartouche
@example
@code{resend} [@var{turn}]
@end example
@end cartouche

Ask the order scanner to resend a turn report.  The turn argument
defaults to the turn most recently run.

Because of their large size, turn reports other than the most recent may
not be kept by the order scanner.  If you request a report and the
scanner responds that the report cannot be found, then the reports for
that turn were deleted to reclaim disk space.

@node rumor, sail, resend, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{rumor}
@cartouche
@example
@code{rumor} @var{# of lines of text}
@bullet{} time: 0 days
@bullet{} priority: 1
@end example
@end cartouche

Submit an unsigned message to the Game Newsletter.

The @code{rumor} order may be given by a noble or by the player entity.
The identity of the submitting entity will not appear with the
message; @code{rumor} posts are anonymous.

The number of lines in the entry should be given as an argument to
@code{rumor}, followed by the text of the entry.  For example: here is a
rumor someone submitted.

@example
@group
RUMOR 3
As whispered from ear to ear in the great hall of the Chateau Olympique:
Q:  Why do so many people take an instant dislike to Oleg the Loudmouth?
A:  Saves time.
@end group
@end example

Take care to carefully count the lines of text in the post.  If the
wrong number of lines is given, your noble may end up posting
his orders instead of executing them.

Alternatively, one may specify 0 for the lines of text argument,
and terminate the message with the END keyword:

@example
@group
RUMOR 0
As whispered from ear to ear in the great hall of the Chateau Olympique:
Q:  Why do so many people take an instant dislike to Oleg the Loudmouth?
A:  Saves time.
END
@end group
@end example

Take great care when using the 0 lines/END keyword feature.  If you
forget the END, or mistype it, none of the orders following the
@code{rumor} command will execute.  Instead, they will be published in
the newsletter.  This is obviously very bad, so if you intend to use the
END keyword to avoid having to count lines, please be careful.

Each line of posted text must be less than 78 characters long, or
the post will be rejected.

Editorial guidelines for submissions to the newsletter:

@enumerate
@item
No profanity.

@item
No personal insults to other humans (in-character
roleplaying insults are fine).

@end enumerate

In some cases, the Times pays money for submissions.  If so, it will be
noted in the Game description.

@node sail, seek, rumor, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{sail}
@cartouche
@example
@code{sail} @var{direction or destination} [@dots{}]
@bullet{} time: varies
@bullet{} priority: 4
@end example
@end cartouche

Pilot a ship in the given direction, or to the specified location.  If a
location is specified, there must be a direct route to it from the
current location of the ship.

Compass points may be abbreviated: @samp{n}, @samp{s}, @samp{e}, @samp{w}.

The Sailing [1001] subskill of Shipcraft [1000] is required to use the
@code{sail} order.

The noble issuing the sail order must be the ship's captain,
i.e. the noble must be the first unit listed in the @samp{Seen here}
report of the ship.

The @code{sail} order will fail if the ship is overloaded.  Use
@code{drop} to throw items overboard if necessary.

Multiple destinations or directions may be given as arguments to
@code{sail}.  If the first fails, the next will be tried, until a
passable route is found, or @code{sail} runs out of arguments.

For example, @samp{@code{sail} n e w} would first try to sail north.  If
travel north was not possible for any reason, east would next be tried,
then west.  In this way exploring units can attempt to deal with the
case of running into an impassable ocean route, or a coast.

@node seek, sell, sail, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{seek}
@cartouche
@example
@code{seek} [@var{who}]
@bullet{} time: 7 days
@bullet{} priority: 3
@end example
@end cartouche

Seek for a hidden noble.  Nobles may be hidden because of fog
lying over a province, or through the application of stealth or magical
skills.

Hidden nobles can not be interacted with by a unit unless they
@code{contact} the unit first, or the unit successfully finds them with
@code{seek}.  The @code{seek} order will return immediately if the
noble is visible, or has already been found with a previous
@code{seek} order.

If a noble is specified, there is a 50% chance that the noble
will be found during each of the seven days the order is being executed.

This chance is reduced by 5% for each experience level of [1290] Conceal
Self the hidden noble possesses (provided, of course, that he is using
the skill to conceal himself).  For example, a noble with experience
level 4 in [1290] Conceal Self will be spotted only 30% (50-4*5) of the
time.

The chance to spot a hidden noble is increased by 5% for each experience
level of [1901] Spot Hidden Noble possessed by the noble performing the
seek.  For example, a noble with experience level 3 in [1901] Spot Hidden
Noble would have an additional 15% chance to spot a hidden noble.

If the @var{who} argument is not given, @code{seek} will seek for any
hidden nobles present.  In this case there will be one-half the
normal chance of finding a hidden noble during each of the seven days.

If a unit found with @code{seek} moves, the contact information is lost,
and the unit again becomes inaccessible.

Hidden units are not shown in the location report, even if their
presence has been revealed through @code{contact} or @code{seek}.

Related orders: @ref{contact}

@node sell, split, seek, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{sell}
@cartouche
@example
@code{sell} @var{item} @var{qty} @var{price} [@var{have-left}]
@bullet{} time: 0 days
@bullet{} priority: 1
@end example
@end cartouche

Sell @var{quantity} of the given item for @var{max-price} each.

If @var{quantity} is zero, any pending @code{sell} order for the
indicated item will be canceled.

Only one pending @code{sell} order may be active for each item at a
time.  If two @code{sell} orders are issued for the same item, and the
first has not yet completed, the second @code{sell} order will replace
the first.

Buys and sells are only matched in cities, where markets may be found to
execute trades.  However, @code{buy} and @code{sell} may be issued
anywhere.

Trades only occur at the end of the day.  Therefore, you must stay in a
location for at least one day to execute a trade.  If you step into a
market, issue a @code{buy} or @code{sell}, and then leave immediately,
no trade will occur.  To be certain to stay at least one day, you may
issue a @ref{wait} command.

@c @group
Example:

@example
@group
> sell 79 3 5
Try to sell three iron [79] for 5 gold each.
@end group
@end example

@c @group
If there is a buyer of iron in the city, buying for 5 gold or more, the
trade will be executed:

@example
@group
1: Sold three iron [79] for 5 gold.
@end group
@end example

@c @group
Otherwise, the sell will be placed on the noble's pending trades
list:

@example
@group
Pending trades:

trade    price    qty   item
-----    -----    ---   ----
 sell        5      3   iron [79]
@end group
@end example

@c @group
At the end of the turn, the sell order will appear in the city's
market report:

@example
@group
Market report:

trade    who    price    qty   item
-----    ---    -----    ---   ----
 sell   2019        5      3   iron [79]
@end group
@end example

A trade will match between a buyer and a seller if the buyer's price is
greater than or equal to the seller's price.  The actual price that the
trade will be made at is the seller's price.

Have-left is an amount of the item that noble will keep and not
sell.  For instance, if the unit issued @samp{@code{sell} 79 10 15 5},
this would mean "Sell ten iron for 15 gold each, but keep 5 iron for
myself."  If there noble only have ten iron, this order would put
five up them up for sale.

@node split, stack, sell, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{split}
@cartouche
@example
@code{split} @var{bytes} @var{lines}
@bullet{} time: 0 days
@bullet{} priority: 1
@end example
@end cartouche

Split large turn reports before mailing them.

Some mail networks and online services have restrictions on how large
an email message may be.  Some typical limits which may be encountered
are 5,000 lines, 50k, and 64k.  Since Olympia turn reports can be
arbitrarily large, players with such restrictions on their incoming
email may have trouble getting their reports.  Reports may be truncated,
or not delivered at all.

The @code{split} order asks Olympia to divide turn reports into several pieces
before mailing them.  The @code{lines} parameter, if nonzero, gives a maximum
number of lines to allow in a turn report section.  The @code{bytes} parameter,
if nonzero, gives a maximum number of bytes to allow in a turn report
section.  Reports will be split at the first of these limits reached.

Note that headers added by the operating system add to the size of a
message after it has been mailed.  Leaving 2000 bytes or 20 lines leeway
before your desired limit is a good idea.

@c @group
For example, suppose your incoming messages are truncated at 50k bytes.
Issue the order:

@example
@group
split 0 48000
@end group
@end example

This will cause messages to be split after the first 48,000 bytes.
Lines are ignored for the purposes of splitting.

@c @group
If your messages are rejected if they are larger than 64k or 5,000
lines, whichever is less, issue the order:

@example
@group
split 4980 62000	# note 20 line / 2000 byte margin
@end group
@end example

@c @group
To turn off report splitting, issue the order:

@example
@group
split 0 0
@end group
@end example

Reports will be split on line boundaries (lines will not be split
in the middle).  "[part n of total]" will be added to the Subject:
line of each section.  For example,

@example
@group
Subject: Olympia turn 1 report [part 1 of 3]
@end group
@end example

The SPLIT order is parsed by the order scanner, so it takes effect
immediately, rather than when the next turn runs.  Suppose you
received a turn report which was truncated because of a mail size
limit of 32k.  You could request a resend of your turn report, split
into sections, with the following message to the order scanner:

@example
@group
begin <your player id>
split 0 30000		# split at 32k, with 2k leeway
resend			# resend my last report to me
@end group
@end example

@node stack, stop, split, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{stack}
@cartouche
@example
@code{stack} @var{noble}
@bullet{} time: 0 days
@bullet{} priority: 1
@end example
@end cartouche

Stack beneath the specified noble.  If the noble is already
stacked beneath another unit, the noble will first unstack before
stacking with the new noble.

@c @group
Example: Two nobles, Feasel and Osswid, are in the same location:

@example
@group
Seen here:
   Osswid [5499]
   Feasel the Wicked [502]
@end group
@end example

@c @group
If Feasel issued the order @samp{@code{stack} 5499}, he would stack
beneath Osswid:

@example
@group
Seen here:
   Osswid [5499], accompanied by:
      Feasel the Wicked [502]
@end group
@end example

Nobles may also stack beneath garrisons and controlled units.

Any attempt to stack will fail if you do not have "admit" permissions
(@ref{admit}).

@node stop, study, stack, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{stop}
@cartouche
@example
@code{stop}
@end example
@end cartouche

Interrupt a command left running at the end of a turn.  Must be the
first order queued for a unit.

@c @group
For example, suppose on day 28 a unit begins an explore command.
Explore takes seven days, so as of the end of the turn, it will still
have four days left before it completes.  The order template for the
unit will list the executing command:

@example
@group
unit 5499  # Osswid
   # > explore (executing for four more days)
@end group
@end example

@c @group
The player may interrupt this command with the @code{stop} order, and
begin unit 5499 executing a new set of orders (say, beginning with a
@code{move}) on day 1 of the next turn:

@example
@group
unit 5499  # Osswid
   # > explore (executing for four more days)
   stop
   move
   @dots{}
@end group
@end example

(Remember that @samp{#} begins a comment in the orders, from the
@samp{#} to the end of the line).

The @code{stop} order will interrupt the executing @code{explore} before
day 1 begins on the next turn.  Some commands, such as @code{collect},
will give partial results; the unit will have whatever it has already
collected.  Other orders, such as @code{explore}, give no partial
benefit, and the three days already invested in exploration will be
wasted.

If a noble executing a @code{move} order is interrupted with
@code{stop}, the noble will return to the original location, as if
no travel had taken place.

@node study, take, stop, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{study}
@cartouche
@example
@code{study} @var{skill} [@var{study points flag}]
@bullet{} time: 7 days
@bullet{} priority: 3
@end example
@end cartouche

Study the given skill for one week.

If the skill has been studied before, learning will continue.
Otherwise, the noble must meet the requirements necessary to begin
learning the skill.

To begin study of a skill requires the following:

@itemize @bullet
@item Payment of 100 gold to begin study.
@item For category skills, a source of instruction.

@itemize @minus
@item A noble teaching the skill.
@item A city teaching the skill.
@item A book of instruction in the skill.
@item Study points.
@end itemize
@end itemize

To complete the study of a skill requires the following:

@itemize @bullet
@item Payment of Noble Points to learn advanced skills
@end itemize

To use your study points (see @ref{Study Points}) to learn a skill, you
must provide the study point flag after the skill to be studied.  Just
provide a "1" to indicate that you wish to use study points:

@example        
                study 1000 1
@end example

This prevents you from inadvertantly spending your study points (e.g.,
when you thought you were in a tower with a teacher, but he never showed
up).

Note that multiple @code{study} orders during a turn yield diminishing
results:

@itemize @minus
@item First week: 7/7
@item Second week: 4/7
@item Third week: 2/7
@item Fourth week: 1/7
@end itemize

@xref{Skills} for more detailed information about @code{study}.

