@node ungarrison, unload, train, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{ungarrison}
@cartouche
@example
@code{ungarrison} [@var{garrison}]
@bullet{} time: 1 day
@bullet{} priority: 3
@end example
@end cartouche

Disband the garrison in the current province.  The noble removing
the garrison must be a member of a faction which has rulership over the
province.

If a specific garrison is given as an argument to @code{ungarrison},
only that garrison will be disbanded.  This can be useful as a safety
check, in case a failed @code{move} order might cause the wrong garrison
unit to be disbanded.

The garrison's men will be transferred to the noble issuing
@code{ungarrison}.

@c @group
Examples:

@example
@group
ungarrison 5611         # remove Garrison [5611] from this province
ungarrison              # remove any garrison from this province
@end group
@end example


@node unload, unstack, ungarrison, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{unload}
@cartouche
@example
@code{unload}
@bullet{} time: 0 days
@bullet{} priority: 3
@end example
@end cartouche

Unload all passengers from a ship.  May only be used by the captain of a
ship.  Every noble not in the captain's stack will disembark from
the ship.

Passengers may only be unloaded while the ship is docked in a port.
They will not jump off a ship at sea.

@node unstack, use, unload, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{unstack}
@cartouche
@example
@code{unstack} [@var{who}]
@bullet{} time: 0 days
@bullet{} priority: 1
@end example
@end cartouche

When used without an argument, @code{unstack} removes the noble from
being stacked beneath another noble:

@c @group
Before:

@example
@group
Osswid the Constructor [5499], accompanied by:
   Feasel the Wicked [502]
   Captain McCook [2019], with five workers
@end group
@end example

@example
@group
502: > unstack
@end group
@end example

@c @group
After:

@example
@group
Osswid the Constructor [5499]
Feasel the Wicked [502], accompanied by:
   Captain McCook [2019], with five workers
@end group
@end example

A stack leader may give an argument to @code{unstack}, specifying a unit
to be dropped from the stack:

@c @group
Before:

@example
@group
Osswid the Constructor [5499], accompanied by:
   Feasel the Wicked [502]
   Captain McCook [2019], with five workers
@end group
@end example

@example
@group
5499: > unstack 502
@end group
@end example

@c @group
After:

@example
@group
Osswid the Constructor [5499]
Feasel the Wicked [502], accompanied by:
   Captain McCook [2019], with five workers
@end group
@end example

Note that in this example [2019] is stacked beneath [502], not [5499].
That is why Captain McCook remains with Feasel when Feasel unstacks.
@xref{Stacking} for more details on hierarchical stacks.

A special case of @code{unstack} is invoked if the noble specifies
itself as the argument.  In this case, the noble will drop out of the
stack alone, leaving behind both those stack above as well as below:

@c @group
Before:

@example
@group
Osswid the Constructor [5499], accompanied by:
   Feasel the Wicked [502], accompanied by:
      Captain McCook [2019], with five workers
@end group
@end example

@example
@group
502: > unstack 502
@end group
@end example

@c @group
After:

@example
@group
Osswid the Constructor [5499], accompanied by:
   Captain McCook [2019], with five workers
Feasel the Wicked [502]
@end group
@end example

The effect on the stack in this case is the same as if Feasel had died
or been captured in battle.

More examples:

@c @group
Before:

@example
@group
Osswid the Constructor [5499], accompanied by:
   Feasel the Wicked [502]
@end group
@end example

@c @group
After Feasel unstacks:

@example
@group
Osswid the Constructor [5499]
Feasel the Wicked [502]
@end group
@end example

If other nobles were stacked beneath Feasel, they would remain with
him.

@c @group
Before:

@example
@group
Osswid the Constructor [5499], accompanied by:
   Feasel the Wicked [502], accompanied by:
      Candide [1269]
@end group
@end example

@c @group
If Candide were stacked beneath Feasel, and Feasel unstacked, then:

@example
@group
Osswid the Constructor [5499]
Feasel the Wicked [502], accompanied by:
   Candide [1269]
@end group
@end example

@c @group
On the other hand, if Candide were stacked beneath Osswid, then:

@example
@group
Osswid the Constructor [5499], accompanied by:
   Candide [1269]
Feasel the Wicked [502]
@end group
@end example


@node use, vis_email, unstack, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{use}
@cartouche
@example
@code{use} @var{skill} [@var{arguments} @dots{}]
@bullet{} time: varies
@bullet{} priority: 3
@end example
@end cartouche

Make use of a skill or spell that the noble knows.  Sub-skills
often have a function which is invoked through @code{use}.

@c @group
Category skills do not have direct @code{use} functions.  For example,
one could use the Sailing [1001] skill to sail a ship:

@example
@group
use 1001 west
@end group
@end example

But no use function exists for the category skill, Shipcraft [1000].

This command is also used to control which combat spells are used in
battle.  @xref{Selection of Spells}.

