@node wait, wood, vis_email, Appendix - Command listing
@unnumberedsec @code{wait}
@cartouche
@example
@code{wait} @var{conditions}
@bullet{} time: varies
@bullet{} priority: 1
@end example
@end cartouche

Wait for one of the the specified conditions to occur.  The first
condition which is satisfied will cause the wait command to terminate.
If one of the specified wait conditions is true when the wait order is
issued, no wait will take place, and the order will complete in zero
time.

The following conditions may be waited on:
@table @dfn

@item alone
Wait until the noble is alone in a location, meaning that his stack is
the only stack in the location.  (@xref{guild}.)

@item clear
Wait until it is not foggy, windy or rainy.

@item day @var{n}
Wait until the day of the month is @var{n}, or later.  For example,
"wait day 15" waits until it is the 15th of the month or later.

@item turn @var{n}
Wait until it is turn @var{n}, or later.

@item ferry @var{n}
Wait for the ship @var{n} to sound its horn with the @code{ferry} order.

Units waiting to @code{board} a ferry should use @code{wait ferry}
instead of @code{wait ship}.  This will allow passengers on the ship
time to disembark.  When passenger unloaded is complete, the captain
will sound the ship's horn, and those wishing to @code{board} may
proceed.

Otherwise, those waiting to board may try to get on the ship before the
current load of passengers has left, causing @code{board} orders to fail
because of ship weight limits.

@item flag @var{f} [@var{n}]
Wait until noble @var{n}, or a noble belonging to player
@var{n}, signals with flag @var{f}.  @var{n} defaults to the player
issuing the flag order.  If @var{n} is zero, wait until any noble
signals with flag @var{f}.  @xref{flag} for more details

@item fog
Wait until it is foggy in the noble's province.

@item gold @var{n}
Wait until the noble has at least @var{n} gold

@item item @var{n} @var{q}
Wait until the noble has at least quantity @var{q} of item @var{n}

@item loc @var{n}
Wait until arrival at the given location.

@item not
Invert the sense of the following condition.

@item owner
Wait until the noble is the first noble in the location list.

@item rain
Wait until it is raining in the noble's province.

@item ship @var{n}
Wait until the specified ship arrives in port.

@item shiploc @var{n}

Many players have been bitten by using @code{wait loc} while they're on a
ship to wait for the ship's arrival at a particular port.  Don't do this!
@code{wait loc} waits for the noble to arrive at a particular location.  If
the noble is on a ship, @i{the ship} is the location the noble is in, not
the ship's location.

Use @code{wait shiploc} to wait for the ship's arrival at a particular
place.

@item stack @var{n}
Wait until the noble and unit @var{n} are members of the same stack.
Position within the stack is not important; The condition is true
whenever @var{n} and the noble share a common stack leader.

@item time @var{n}
Wait for @var{n} days to elapse

@item top
Wait until the unit becomes a stack leader.  This could happen if the
units's current stack leader unstacked or promoted the unit.

@item unit @var{n}
Wait until the noble and the specified unit are in the same location

@item wind
Wait until it is windy in the noble's province.

@item teacher @var{n}
Wait until a source of specific instruction for the specified skill is
available.  This can be a book or a teacher.  Note that if you wait for
a subskill (e.g., 3401), this wait condition will not be satisfied by
someone teaching the skill school (e.g., 3400).  

@end table

@c @group
For example:

@example
@group
1: > wait time 1
1: Wait finished: one day has passed.
2: > wait time 10 day 5
5: Wait finished: today is day 5.
@end group
@end example

The first condition to become true will end the wait.  This can be used
to specify the maximum amount of time that the noble will wait for
something.

@c @group
For instance, suppose we want to wait for [5499] to show up, but we don't
want to wait past day 15.

@example
@group
> wait unit 5499 day 15
@end group
@end example

This order will finish on day 15 or as soon as 5499 shows up, which ever
comes first.  If 5499 is already here when the order is issued, no wait
will take place.  Likewise, if it is already past day 15, no wait will
take place.

Keep in mind that the order priority mechanism eliminates the need to
use waits in many cases.  Consider synchronization in the following
example:

Feasel [502] arrives at Osswid's [5499] location.
Feasel gives Osswid some gold, and then leaves.
Osswid departs after receiving the gold.

@example
@group
unit 502   # Feasel
  move @dots{}
  pay 5499 100
  move @dots{}

unit 5499  # Osswid
  wait unit 502
  move @dots{}
@end group
@end example

The orders above will work; no additional waits are needed.  After the
@code{wait unit} becomes true, both 502's @code{pay} and 5499's
@code{move} are ready to execute.  Since @code{pay} has a lower priority
than @code{move}, @code{pay} will happen first.

This technique also works with @code{stack} and @code{give}, since they
also have a lower priority than @code{move}.

The NOT keyword inverts the sense of the condition which follows.
For example:

@example
@group
> wait not rain time 7
@end group
@end example

Will wait until it is not raining, or for seven days, whichever comes first.

@example
@group
> wait not rain not wind
@end group
@end example

Will wait until it is not raining or not windy.

