Each rowing port accommodates 4 oarsmen.  Each unit of hull may have a
maximum of 3 ports, and each newly-constructed hull comes with one
rowing port.

Rowing a ship at normal speed requires one fully-staffed rowing port per
unit hull.  For example, rowing a 3 unit hull ship at normal speeds
requires that the ship have 3 rowing ports and at least 14 sailors (2 to
man the hull and 4 each for the 3 rowing ports).

Each additional fully-staffed rowing port per unit hull cuts a ship's
rowing travel time by one day.  For example, a 3 unit ship with 6 fully
manned rowing ports would cut its travel time by one day, crossing a 6
day ocean province in just 5 days.

Conversely, if a ship has less than one full-staffed rowing port per
unit hull, it will add one day of travel time.  A ship with less than
one oarsman per unit hull cannot move at all.




