These aliases replace the first item with the second item. For
instance, the alias:

@example
	#define prot_blast 3531
@end example

causes every occurence of "prot_blast" in your commands to be replaced
with "3531".

You may add your own aliases at the beginning of your commands. For
instance, if you have a noble "Maldor" with the id "5499" you could add
the alias

@example
   	#define Maldor 5499
@end example

at the beginning of your orders to cause "Maldor" to be replaced with
"5499".

There are a couple of problems you should be aware of if you use the
preprocessor.

First, the aliases for collecting fish, wood, etc., will not work. If
you try to give the command "fish" it will be replaced with "87" and
you'll get the error:

@example
>line 105: unrecognized command: 87
@end example

Second, the preprocessor works on your entire turn, which means if you
submit the command:

@example
rumor 1
All that glitters is not gold.
@end example

what you'll actually see as a rumor is something like:

@example
rumor 1
All that glitters is not  1 .
@end example

because the preprocessor will replace "gold" with "1".

For advanced users, the preprocessor used is the Gnu C preprocessor.

